<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada to Send 800 Soldiers to Balkans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Canada is sending 800 troops to
the Balkans at the request of NATO, Prime Minister Jean Chretien
said Tuesday in the Commons, Canada's lower House of Parliament.
</P>
<P>
"I now rise to inform the House that Canada has received a
formal request from NATO to initiate the deployment of our portion
of the peace implementation force to the former Yugoslav Republic
of Macedonia," said the Canadian prime minister.
</P>
<P>
"Today, we intend to inform NATO that the government agrees to
this request," he added.
</P>
<P>
"These troops--some 800 in total-- will join 12,000 NATO troops
who have already been pre-positioned in the Former Yugoslav
Republic of Macedonia to move into Kosovo as part of a peace
settlement," said Chretien.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister assured all members of Parliament "that the
purpose of this deployment does not extend beyond what has already
been debated in this House....if there is a NATO request to deploy
Canadian troops in combat, the House will be consulted before any
final decision is taken."  
</P>
</TEXT>
