<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Stock Markets Set New Records </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON April 27 (Xinhua) - Soaring bank, oil and telecom stocks
and a strong showing on Wall Street and Asia overnight fueled a
rally in European markets Tuesday with London and Paris setting
new records.
</P>
<P>
The FTSE 100 finished 90 points higher at 6593.6, a gain of 1.4
percent. This eclipsed the previous record close of 6515.3, set on
19 April, while the FTSE 100 peaked at 6635.9, an all time
intra-day best.
</P>
<P>
Strength in US technology shares boosted early sentiment in
London, after the Nasdaq raced to a new record high on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Positive momentum built up gradually in the City, as the FTSE
100 had scored a century around midday, with the session's best
coming shortly before Wall Street opened.
</P>
<P>
"We've been following Wall Street for some time and will
continue to do so, but US markets are looking pretty mixed, with
the S&AMP;P little changed and the Nasdaq lower," said James Dewhurst,
senior salesman at UK brokerage Charterhouse.
</P>
<P>
French shares shot up 2.49 percent, or 106 points, to finish at
4390.92 on the CAC 40, passing the previous closing record of
4388.48 set July 17,1998.
</P>
<P>
The rally was underpinned by sharp gains in France Telecom and
Alcatel, which jumped 3.46 percent to 79.25 euros and 3.67 percent
to 121.5 euros, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Conglomerate Lagardere led the CAC 40 advancers, rocketing 9.25
percent to 36.50 euros in Paris.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, the electronically traded Xetra Dax breached key
technical resistance at 5300 to finish 1.8 percent higher, at
5364.81.
</P>
<P>
Deutsche Telekom gained more than 5 percent to 37.50 despite
talk that European regulators may thwart its planned merger with
Italy's Telecom Italia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
