<HEADLINE> U.S. Consumer Confidence Rises in April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Consumer confidence, a key
indicator of future U.S. economic activity rose nearly a full
point in April for the sixth straight month, the Conference Board,
a private research group, reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Consumer Confidence Index rose 0.9 point to 134.9 from a
revised 134 in March, the group said. The Expectations Index rose
to 108 from 105.5.
</P>
<P>
"Consumers are showing no signs of pessimism and no signs of
curbing their strong spending habits," said Lynn Franco, Associate
Director of the Board's Consumer Research Center. "They will
continue to contribute significantly to this record-breaking
economic expansion."
</P>
<P>
The Consumer Confidence survey is based on a representative
sample of 5000 U.S. households and consumer sentiment is an
important economic indicator because consumer spending accounts
for two-thirds of the nation's overall economic activity. The
survey polls consumers on matters ranging from job prospects to
buying plans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
