<HEADLINE> Egypt's Progress in Economic Development Hailed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Egypt is one of the emerging
economies in the world with vast prospects for foreign
investments, according to an annual report issued Tuesday by the
Arab-German Chamber of Commerce in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
The report said the Egyptian government is exerting growing
efforts to turn the country into a trade and financial hub in the
Middle East.
</P>
<P>
The report cited Egypt's strong commitment to economic
liberalization and privatization, the country's geographical
position and its enormous technological potentials as factors that
will benefit the Egyptian economy in the future.
</P>
<P>
Egypt started economic reforms in 1991 to loosen control over
and privatize the state-run enterprises. Since then, its gross
domestic product has grown from 2 percent to more than 5 percent,
inflation has fallen from 20 percent to under 4 percent and
foreign currency reserves have climbed to 20 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Till 1998, Egypt had privatized more than one third of the 314
state-run enterprises selected for the process starting in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The report said Egypt's stock exchange is one of the most
active and fastest growing bourses in the world, with a market
capital of over 20 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The report recommended Egypt increase exports to reduce its
trade deficit. In the 1997-98 fiscal year ending on June 30 last
year, Egypt's exports were registered at 5.331 billion dollars
while its imports amounted to 16.552 billion dollars, with a
deficit of 11.221 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
