<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Moldovan Parliament's President Visits Romania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, April 27 (Xinhua) -- There are no major hindrances
to conclude a bilateral treaty between Romania and Repubic of
Moldova, the President of the Moldovan Parliament Dumitru Diacov
said here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Dumitru Diacov told a press conference here that the "future
Romania-Repubic of Moldova treaty will have to cover the current
reality of the ties between the two countries".
</P>
<P>
In his opinion, "there are no major hindrances to conclude such
a treaty which could establish the legal frame of a co-operation
and remove certain suspicions".
</P>
<P>
Dumitru Diacov also said that the two sides agreed in a meeting
with the Foreign Ministry on the fact that the experts groups in
the two states should meet as quickly as possible in order to
start negotiations for the conclusion of the treaty.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the chances to return properties to the refugees
from the former Romanian province of Bessarabia (the Republic of
Moldova at present) who live in Romania after the second World
War, Diacov said the issue had not been discussed in the Republic
of Moldova until now. Anyway, there is no such possibility because
of a lack of archives which were supposed to prove the legal
status of properties, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Dumitru Diacov arrived on Monday in Bucharest on a two-day
official visit, at the invitation of the Romanian Senate. It is
his first visit in Bucharest after parliamental elections on March
2, 1998. Dumitru Diacov had talks with the President of Romania's
Senate Petre Roman and the Speaker of the Chamber of Deputies Ion
Diaconescu. He also met Romanian President Emil Constantinescu and
Prime Minister Radu Vasile.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral ties between Romania and the Republic of Moldova have
been moving upwards since their establishment on August 29, 1991,
the day of the proclamation of independence of the former Soviet
republic. During the span of time, authorities in the two states
have signed about 40 treaties, agreements and conventions.
However, the conclusion of a political treaty delays, and the
Republic of Moldova is now the only neighbouring country with
which Romania has not signed a basic treaty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
