<HEADLINE> Fifth Round of Four-Party Talks on Korean Peninsula </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Negotiators from China, the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK), South Korea, and the
United States ended the fifth round of talks on the Korean
Peninsula here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In a joint press statement issued at the end of the four-day
talks, the four parties said that they had agreed to continue to
discuss substantive issues and proposals for agenda items of the
two subcommittees at the next session, the sixth one, to be
chaired by China in August.
</P>
<P>
The two subcommittees, established during the fourth session
last January, were meant to discuss respectively tension reduction
on the Korean Peninsula and the establishment of a peace regime
there.
</P>
<P>
During the subcommittee meetings on April 25-26, according to
the statement, detailed substantive views were freely exchanged.
The negotiators admitted that "serious differences in positions
exist".
</P>
<P>
However, "the four parties agreed in the next round to consider
and fashion measures to reduce tension that fit the unique
situation on the Korean Peninsula," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed to take steps in the next round "to explore
further the outlines of a future peace regime on the Korean
Peninsula", according to the statement.
</P>
<P>
The four countries began the talks on the Korean Peninsula in
December 1997 in Geneva. 
</P>
</TEXT>
