<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Signals Recovery, U.S. Paper Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 27 (Xinhua) -- After a year and a half of
recession, Hong Kong is beginning to show signs of recovery, the
Wall Street Journal said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Journal said in a dispatch from Hong Kong that overseas
companies are bidding for and buying sizable stakes in corporate
Hong Kong and property prices are stabilizing.
</P>
<P>
The stock market in Hong Kong has rebounded to its highest
level in 18 months, the paper said, adding that concern about the
Hong Kong dollar has abated.
</P>
<P>
The Journal said even tourism, until recently one of the worst
sectors, is up. Visitor arrivals jumped 13 percent in the first
quarter of this year compared with last year.
</P>
<P>
Those indicators contrast with the gloom among some
business people and economists not that long ago, the paper said.
"They also suggest that recovery is being hastened by the
intangible advantages that Hong Kong wields over many of its Asian
neighbors: minimal red tape, a transparent business environment
and a robust legal system."
</P>
<P>
The Journal said even a negative sign like bankruptcies
illustrates one of Hong Kong's strengths and a transparent and
effective legal system helps to aid recovery. Christopher Howe, a
director of Anglo-Chinese Corporate Finance Ltd. In Hong Kong, was
quoted as saying that in Hong Kong, creditors can collect on bad
debts, and a small but growing number of outside investors have
used the bankruptcy courts to gain control of poorly managed
firms.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the paper said, hard time are forcing some firms to
cut costs and revamp, enhancing their competition in the market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
