<HEADLINE> Greek Political Party Leaders Agree to Form Anti-NATO Front </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The President of Greece's
Democratic Social Movement (DHKKI) Dimitris Tsovolas and the
Secretary-General of the Communist Party of Greece (KKE) Aleka
Papariga agreed during their talks Tuesday that there was a need
to form an anti-NATO front from social and political forces.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after the talks, Tsovolas said that Greece's
progressive parties should back the formation of a broad social
anti-NATO front in order to create obstacles to the inhuman,
barbarous choices of the major Western powers.
</P>
<P>
He had agreed with Papariga on the need for the convening of a
meeting of Greece's political party leaders, so that the parties
could make their positions clear on current developments and, if
possible, formulate a national strategy.
</P>
<P>
He said that his party's stance was that Greece should not
provide facilities to NATO.
</P>
<P>
On her part, Papariga said that the purpose of an anti-NATO
front would be to prepare the Greek people for the difficult days
which were coming.
</P>
<P>
Greece's main opposition New Democracy (ND) leader Costas
Karamanlis and Coalition of the Left President Nikos
Constantopoulos also agreed during their talks last week that
Greece should not become directly or indirectly involved in any
ground operations by NATO in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
They also called for the establishment of a foreign policy
council and a meeting convened of the country's political party
leaders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
