<HEADLINE> Rwanda Hosts Regional Conference on AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 27 (Xinhua) -- A regional conference on AIDS
opened in Rwandan capital Kigali Tuesday, the Rwanda News Agency
(RNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Rwandan Prime Minister Pierre Celestin Rwigema officially
inaugurated the Great Lakes Initiative Against AIDS which was
created in March 1998 in Kampala, Uganda, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The launching ceremony was presided over by many dignitaries of
the government, and health ministers from Burundi, Uganda, Rwanda,
and the representative of their Tanzanian colleague.
</P>
<P>
A delegation from the Democratic Republic of Congo -- it was
not specified whether it was governmental or rebel -- was expected
to arrive for the conference.
</P>
<P>
All delegates agreed that AIDS was a big threat to the public
health in the Great Lakes region, and called upon each country to
work to check the pandemic.
</P>
<P>
Rwandan Minister of Health, Ezechias Rwabuhihi, stressed that
in the Great Lakes region, over 4.3 million people suffer from
AIDS.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. AIDS Executive Director, Peter Piot, said that
although the above number is scaring, there is still a way of
fighting the disease because the leaders of the continent are
aware of its seriousness. 
</P>
</TEXT>
