<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Countries' Economic Success Acknowledged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOUSTON, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Botswana, Egypt, Ghana, Mauritius
and Namibia have been acknowledged by participants at the
Attracting Capital to Africa Summit now being held here.
</P>
<P>
According to a conference press release on Tuesday, Botswana
stood out as it has experienced one of the fastest rates of growth
in Sub-Saharan Africa, with a 7 percent expansion in 1998.
</P>
<P>
With successive balance of payment surpluses and substantial
foreign exchange reserves, the 1.5 million population country
represents a healthy market for exporters.
</P>
<P>
Botswana has adopted a strategy of sustainable economic
diversification, focusing on the growth of manufacturing, tourism
and financial sectors, thus reducing dependency on mineral
revenues.
</P>
<P>
Egypt was praised for its political stability and reform of its
extensive public holdings. It is focusing on improving export
competitiveness, liberalizing its trading regime, encouraging
private sector growth, eliminating obstacles to doing business and
improving investment environment.
</P>
<P>
Ghana's Investment Code encourages foreign investment,
guarantees the free transferability of dividends, loan repayments,
licensing fees and the repatriation of capital.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investors are not subject to differential treatment on
taxes, prices, or access to foreign exchange, import and credit.
</P>
<P>
Mauritius' political, legal and economic systems are seen among
the most advanced in the region. Its telecommunications and banking
infrastructure support sophisticated trade and financing
activities.
</P>
<P>
The country's economic performance has been impressive for the
past 15 years, with real growth averaging 7 percent between
1985-1990 and 5.4 percent during the last six years.
</P>
<P>
Namibia's strengths include a modern infrastructure, a good
business climate and economic and political stability.
</P>
<P>
The government is committed to attracting foreign investment,
providing secure legal framework and a range of incentives to
investors.
</P>
<P>
Botswana President Festus Mogae, Egypt's Ambassador to the
United States Ahmed Maher El Sayed, Ghana President Jerry John
Rawlings, Mauritius Prime Minister Navinchandra Ramgoolam and
Namibia President Sam Nujoma have received Global Marketplace
Award issued by U.S. Corporate Council on Africa on Monday and
Tuesday respectively.
</P>
<P>
The dignitaries joined representatives from two dozens of other
African countries in a five-day forum to exchange views with U.S.
government officials and private sector representatives on trade
and investment expansion in Africa. The conference ends on
Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
