<HEADLINE> Romania: Nuclear Station Stopped Working Due to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The first and the only
generating unit of the Cernavoda nuclear power station stopped
working, late on Monday, because of a mechanical breakdown of the
water supply, the Nuclearelectrica National Company AS informed
here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
It was the first incident of this kind since the unit was put
into operation in 1996. The breakdown has not caused a surge in
radiation level and had no impact over the the environment or the
population, according to the local specialists.
</P>
<P>
This unexpected break occurred after 141 days of the station's
functioning around the clock. The station is to be closed for 36
hours to have mechanical breakdown repaired, said sources of the
company.
</P>
<P>
The Cernavoda Station, located on the east bank of the Danube
River, 170 kilometers east of Bucharest, is Romania's first
nuclear station. It was designed to be composed of five generating
units, each with a power of 700,000 kwh.
</P>
<P>
The first unit of the station was put into use in 1996,
following delays to the project because of financial problems. The
unit provides ten percent of the total electric energy production
of Romania.
</P>
<P>
The Romanian government has given priority to the construction
of the station's second generating unit that could go into
operation in the year 2000 if the funds could be guaranteed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
