<HEADLINE> UN on Humanitarian Impact of Possible Fuel Embargo  Against FRY </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 27 (Xinhua) --There would be two
immediate humanitarian concerns over the possible fuel embargo on
the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia (FRY), a senior U.N. official
said here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Briefing the United Nations Security Council on the latest
humanitarian situation in FRY after NATO launched its airstrikes a
month ago, U.N. Under-Secretary-General for Humanitarian Affairs,
Vieira de Mello, said the possible fuel embargo would further
restrict the ability for international humanitarian agencies to
provide assistance to civilians with the FYR.
</P>
<P>
The insecurity within the country and the destruction of the
transportation infrastructure had made it extremely difficult to
provide assistance, and several U.N. agencies had highlighted that
a fuel embargo would render the provision of humanitarian
assistance even more complicated, Mello said.
</P>
<P>
Mello said the embargo would adversely affect the welfare of
civilians throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
The fuel embargo would impact the civilian population first,
and that the stated objective, an impact on the Yugoslav forces,
would take more time, Mello said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the current shortage of fuel and the impact of an
embargo, would of course severely hamper the agricultural sector
in FRY, and render this year's sowing and harvest well nigh
impossible, Mello added.
</P>
<P>
During the summit over the weekend, NATO countries agreed to
impose an oil embargo on FRY, an apparent bid to jepordize the
military forces of FRY. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
