<HEADLINE> UN on Humanitarian Impact of NATO Bombing in FRY </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 27 (Xinhua) -- NATO's bombing campaign
had had serious humanitarian repercussions for civilians within
the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia (FRY), a senior U.N. official
said here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Briefing the United Nations Security Council on the
humanitarian situation in FRY after NATO launched its airstrikes a
month ago, U.N. Under-Secretary-General General Vieira de Mello,
said according to Belgrade, as at April 21, there had been 7,200
NATO air strikes in which 517 civilians were alleged to have been
killed with some 4,500 civilians injured.
</P>
<P>
The aerial bombardment of industrial, oil and chemical plants
in the regions of Topola, Vojvodina, Pancevo and Novi Sad had
repeatedly resulted in widespread ground and air pollution, and
Yugoslav health and environmental officials had warned of a
possible ecological emergency that would have significantly
adverse effects for the residents in these area, Mello noted.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav authorities also claimed that the strikes had
caused extensive damage to the infrastructure of the country, and
had severely disrupted the population's ability to secure their
own sustenance, Mello said.
</P>
<P>
The airstrikes had reportedly damaged and destroyed water
supply systems, power stations and telecommunications
installations, Mello continued.
</P>
<P>
A protracted air campaign was bound to have a dramatic impact
in the psychological, social and economic conditions of the
Yugoslav population, Mello added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
