<DOCNO> XIE19990428.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romania: Former President Basks in Highest Run of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Leader of the Party of Social
Democracy of Romania Ion Iliescu could return to the highest
office in the state if the general elections took place in the
period immediately ahead, reported the official Rompres news
agency on Tuesday, citing outcome of a recent opinion poll.
</P>
<P>
Ion Iliescu, president of Romania 1990 through 1996 would
benefit from 37 percent of the voters' graces, by 16 percent more
that the present head of state Emil Constantinescu, who now ranks
second in the top of favorable opinions, followed by the leader
of the Alliance for Romania, Teodor Melescanu, 21 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to the polster's findings, 32 percent of the
interviewed would vote for the Party of Social Democracy led by
Iliescu in parliamentary polls, the party is now the largest in
opposition. The ruling Romanian Democratic Convention would enjoy
only 24 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to the survey 40.6 percent say that in 1996 they
picked up the wrong parliamentarians, 38.8 percent say that none of
the post-communist governments has scored notable successes, 37
percent say that from 1990 until 1996 Romania witnessed its
biggest progress since the 1989 Revolution, and 10 percent believe
that Romania has something to gain since the present coalition
took over the rule in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The survey was carried out by Romania's National Institute for
Opinion Study and Marketing over April 13-15. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
