<HEADLINE> Southeast European Transport Ministers Meet in Athens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Transport and Communications
Ministers from southeast European countries began here Tuesday a
meeting aimed at adoption of a multilateral accord on road
transports that would be a key step forward in regional
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The 11 ministers from Albania, Bosnia-Herzegovina, Bulgaria,
Croatia, Greece, Hungary, Macedonia, Moldova, Romania, Slovenia
and Turkey were expected to adopt a memorandum of understanding
containing the principles for policy and action in facilitating
transports, such as liberalization of the road transport of goods,
membership in international accords, so that all the countries
would follow the same rules of transport and transit, adoption of
a Southeast European Cooperative Initiative (SECI) weighing
standard, abolition of special fees, and the operation of an
information system on pricing and taxation, the semi-official
Athens News Agency (ANA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Greece's Transport and Communications Minister Tasos Mantelis
said at the meeting that the transport sector was emerging as an
important factor of economic cooperation and development among the
countries of southeastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
The SECI aimed at getting rid of obstacles and distortions in
the market of international road transport of merchandise that had
serious repercussions on Greece in particular due to its
geographic position. 
</P>
