<HEADLINE> UK Eager to Welcome Back "Isolated" Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 27 (Xinhua) - British Foreign Secretary Robin
Cook said on Tuesday that he wanted Russia to be part of the
solution, not the problem, in the Kosovo conflict.
</P>
<P>
"They are now seeking a way back from isolation and we welcome
that. We want Russia to be part of the solution," he said in an
interview to BBC Radio.
</P>
<P>
Cook's remarks were regarded as a part of the efforts by the
western alliance to bring Moscow on side as it is seen to carry
influence with Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
"When we have that peace in Kosovo, I would want Russia to be
there with us. After all, they were there with us in Bosnia," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"In the private conversations of the past two weeks, both with
the United States and ourselves, Russia has made it very clear
that it does want to try and be positive and constructive," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Cook stressed that the NATO alliance was not planning an
invasion of Kosovo against armed resistance by the Serb Army.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Vladimir Andreyev, the press attache in the Russian
Embassy in London, said that a Nato invasion of Kosovo could push
Russia "too far".
</P>
<P>
Andreyev said NATO must stop the bombing and resume talks. He
stressed that "anger and outrage" still existed in Moscow over
Nato's strikes against Serbia.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Russia and NATO have become strained as NATO
plans for an oil embargo against Serbia clash with the Russians'
insistence that they will continue to ship oil to the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
Mr Andreyev said attempts to stop Russian ships reaching Serbia
would be very dangerous and "would be close to an act of war".
</P>
