<HEADLINE> Cholera Kills 200 in S. W. Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Cholera has killed more than
200 people since last Wednesday in Dinsor town in Somalia's
southwestern region of Bay, local authorities said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The main traditional leader of the town, Ugas Sidow Hajji
Mohamed, told Xinhua via VHF radio that his people are incredibly
dying in great numbers and that the situation is alarming.
</P>
<P>
According to the local authorities, the average death rate is
20 people per day and the disease is especially rampant in eight
villages and the town of Dinsor itself where people are fallen
from the disease in dozens everyday.
</P>
<P>
The spread of the disease has further been facilitated by the
new influx of refugees arriving in Dinsor and its surrounding
areas within Bay and Bakol regions.
</P>
<P>
Ugas said that over 2,000 destitute families displaced by the
droughts and insecurity are now draining out the resources of
Dinsor town.
</P>
<P>
He noted that thousands of people are suffering from serious
food shortage in the region after the droughts had prolonged more
than expected and the past harvests were extremely poor.
</P>
<P>
Lack of proper quarantine is also attributed to the spread of
the disease, he said.
</P>
<P>
The local health authorities in Dinsor town said there has been
no international response to their plight other than the World
Health Organization which offered them 40 crates of the
anti-dehydration solution besides the American IMC which provided
chlorine for purifying the potable water in the town. 
</P>
</TEXT>
