Speaking at a Freedom Day rally in Umtata shortly before his
departure, Mandela reiterated that the South African government
would continue its effort to promote relations with the world.
</P>
<P>
Freedom Day marked the first all-race election in South Africa
in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Mandela, who is flying in the presidential falcon jet, will be
accompanied throughout by Foreign Minister Alfred Nzo, who is now
in Washington, the United States.
</P>
<P>
Mandela would also have Trade Minister Alec Erwin with him in
Moscow, and a high-powered delegation from the local business
sector, including mining groups and major manufacturers, a
spokesman for the Department of Foreign Affairs said.
</P>
<P>
Mandela, who will retire after the election in June, has
repeatedly postponed a Moscow visit since he assumed the
presidency in 1994. He is expected to sign a declaration of
friendly relations between Pretoria and Moscow.
</P>
<P>
He is due to visit Hungary on April 30, Pakistan on May 4, and
China on the fifth of this month. He will be back in South Africa
on May 8. 
