<HEADLINE> 4 Iraqi Civilians Killed in U.S., British Raids </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Four Iraqi civilians were killed
and several others injured on Tuesday in U.S. and British
warplanes attacks on Iraqi targets, an Iraqi military spokesman
announced.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that at 14:50 (1050 GMT), 11 formations of
enemy warplanes coming from Turkish airspace bombed some civilian
facilities and military sites in Neineva province.
</P>
<P>
He added Iraqi air defenses fired missiles at the enemy planes,
and according to a report by observation posts, one enemy plane
might have been hit as black smoke could be seen emanating from it.
</P>
<P>
Iraq declared several times in the past that its air defenses
had downed U.S. and British warplanes violating its airspace, but
failed to present relevant evidence.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Britain denied this kind of Iraqi claims every
time, saying all their planes enforing the no-fly zones returned
to their bases in Turkey, or in Saudi Arabia or Kuwait safely.
</P>
<P>
Since mid-December, clashes between U.S. and British jets
patrolling the no-fly zones and the Iraqi air defenses have
almost become daily occurrence.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-led western allies imposed the no-fly zones in
Iraq following the 1991 Gulf War with a claimed aim of
protecting the Kurds in the north and the Shiite Muslims in
the south from "Baghdad's suppression."
</P>
<P>
Iraq has declared that it does not recognize these
restricted zones and vowed to continue confronting any allied
plane violating its airspace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
