<HEADLINE> Saudi Defense Minister Starts Three-Nation Tour </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Defense and Aviation
Minister Sultan Ibn Abdul-Aziz on Tuesday kicked off a tour of
Tunis, Iran and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Tunisian embassy sources in Riyadh said Sultan, who is also
Second Deputy Prime Minister, will discuss with Tunisian President
Zine Elabdine Ben Ali and other senior officials means of boosting
bilateral cooperation at all levels.
</P>
<P>
The sources said the two sides will also tackle Arab and
Islamic issues, and ways of reviving Arab solidarity in the face
of pressing challenges.
</P>
<P>
The sources said they believe the visit will give a big push to
the already mounting bilateral cooperation, which they termed as
"tangible" in recent years especially in the economic field.
</P>
<P>
Saudi investments in Tunisia exceed 500 million U.S. dollars.
The two Arab states have set up a joint investment company, which
has invested in over 340 industrial and agricultural projects.
</P>
<P>
The volume of trade between Saudi Arabia and Tunisia was
estimated at 71.2 million dollars in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Sultan's tour to Tunisia will be followed by his first-ever
visit to Iran, where he will hold talks with moderate President
Mohammad Khatami on the Gulf developments, the Middle East peace
process and bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi minister is also expected to meet with Iran's
spiritual leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, former president Ali
Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani and Defense Minister Ali Shamkhani.
</P>
<P>
Both Riyadh and Tehran are believed to have attached great
importance to Sultan's visit since it is coming just before
Khatami's first official visit to Saudi Arabia due in May.
</P>
<P>
Sultan will head on May 3 to Pakistan for talks with Pakistani
Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif on Arab, Islamic and international
developments, including the persistent tension in the South Asia
sub-continent. 
