<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Sales of Existing Homes Hit New High in March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Americans purchased existing
homes at an annual rate of 5.05 million units in March, 0.6
percent higher than February's 5.02 million rate and breaking the
previous record of 5.04 million set in January, the National
Association of Realtors reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The record sales pace at the outset of 1999 follows an
unprecedented year of 4.78 million existing home sales in 1998.
March was the fourth consecutive month that the sales rate topped
5 million.
</P>
<P>
"A combination of factors -- excellent housing affordability
conditions and a strong desire by consumers to buy -- are keeping
the market incredibly strong," said Sharon A. Millett, president
of the real estate group.
</P>
<P>
Unemployment rate near a 29-year low, rising incomes, low
mortgage rates, and solid stock market gains are driving the brisk
home sales.
</P>
<P>
The home-buying boom and consumers' related purchases -- of new
furniture and appliances, for example -- have helped keep the U.S.
economy growing during a time of economic hardship in most other
parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
Regionally, March sales of existing homes were strongest in the
West, rising 2.8 percent to an annual rate of 1.1 million units.
In the Midwest, sales rose 0.9 percent to 1.19 million units.
</P>
<P>
Existing-home sales were unchanged in the South for March,
holding at a rate of 2.05 million units. In the Northeast sales
were weakest, falling 2.7 percent in March, to a rate of 710,000
units.
</P>
<P>
Nationally, the median price of an existing single-family home,
meaning half sold for more and half for less, was 132,7000 dollars
in March, up 4.4 percent from a year ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
