<HEADLINE> Turkey's Poll Results Announced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Turkey's Supreme Board of
Election (YSK) Tuesday announced the results of the parliamentary
and local elections held on April 18.
</P>
<P>
The central-left Democratic Left Party (DSP) led by Prime
Minister Bulent Ecevit took the lead in the 21st parliamentary
elections by winning 22.17 percent of the counted votes of over 37
million registered voters.
</P>
<P>
The right-wing Nationalist Movement Party (MHP) stood the
second by winning 17.90 percent of the votes, the pro-Islamic
Virtue Party (FP) ranked the third with 15.39 percent, the
central-right Motherland Party (ANAP) the fourth with 13.22
percent and the central-right True Path Party (DYP) the fifth
with 12.03 percent of the votes.
</P>
<P>
The central-left Republican People's Party (CHP) only won 8.72
percent of the ballots in the elections.
</P>
<P>
Under Turkey's elections law, a political party can enter the
parliament by winning at least 10 percent of the votes in the
general elections.
</P>
<P>
According to the results, the DSP has gained 136 deputies, the
MHP 129 deputies, the FP 111 deputies, the ANAP 86 deputies and
the DYP 85 deputies in the 550-seat parliament.
</P>
<P>
Over 87.07 percent of the registered voters cast their balloe elections.
</P>
<P>
A total of 20 political parties and independent candidates
competed in the elections.
</P>
<P>
The parliamentary General Assembly will convene on May 2 when
the newly-elected deputies will take oath. 
</P>
</TEXT>
