<HEADLINE> Clinton Expected to Sign Reserve Call-up Order </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 27 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton is
expected to sign a call-up order requested by the Pentagon to have
33,000 reservists to active duty so that NATO would expand its air
armada and quicken the pace of its attacks against Yugoslavia, the
White House said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The president fully recognizes this disrupts lives," White
House spokesman Joe Lockhart said. "But this is what reservists
train for. This is what their mission is. From time to time, they
are called."
</P>
<P>
He said Clinton was expected to sign the call-up later on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The of 33,000 reservists for the call-up was set by Defense
Secretary William Cohen. But the initial requirement may be for a
smaller number. About three-quarters of the total are expected to
be Air Force reserves. Some Army National Guard and REserve
members are likely to be called up to support the Apache
helicopter operations in Albania. A smaller number of Navy and
Marine Corps reservists also are likely to get the call to help
with port management, U.S. officials said.
</P>
<P>
The reserve call-up, which Cohen had predicted would happen a
week ago, has been delayed while NATO worked out agreements with
Hungary and other allied countries to host some of the additional
300 strike and support aircraft requested by Army Gen. Wesley
Clark, the NATO commander.
</P>
<P>
Pentagon spokesman Ken Bacon said on Monday that 30 more Air
Force refueling aircraft had been ordered to Europe in support of
the airstrikes against Yugoslavia. They would leave this weekend
from bases in Arizona, California, Michigan and a fourth,
unspecific state.
</P>
<P>
Also on Monday, Air Force Maj. Gen. Charles Wald told reporters
at the Pentagon that 23 Apache attack helicopters had arrived in
Albanian and were ready to begin attack missions against Yugoslav
army in Kosovo as soon as NATO commanders gave the signal.
</P>
<P>
One of the Apaches crashed near Tirana while on a training
mission early on Tuesday. The cause of the crash was under
investigation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
