<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: UNDP Works Hard to Promote African Development (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOUSTON, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The Africa Bureau of the United
Nations Development Bureau (UNDP) Tuesday concluded a workshop on
"Financial Intermediation and Private Sector in Africa" here
during the five-day "Attracting Capital to Africa Summit", which
began on Saturday last week.
</P>
<P>
The workshop was held to analyze the problems of the private
sector in Africa and suggest approaches to help the continent
deepen its financial mediation and attract foreign direct
investment.
</P>
<P>
"Our aim is to use the event to generate new ideas and
concrete proposals on how to make the African private sector the
engine of economic growth," said Thelma Awori, assistant
administrator of UNDP and director of the U.N. agency's Africa
Bureau.
</P>
<P>
UNDP has co-organized the State of Connecticut Africa Business
Conference 1999 with the State Government on April 20-21, as a
part of an effort to ensure global competitiveness of African
enterprises and entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
UNDP is one of the most widely implanted development agencies
in Africa. With a network of 45 country offices, 10 regional
program offices and two sub-regional offices in Addis Ababa,
Ethiopia, and Harare, Zimbabwe, UNDP focuses on critical issues
ranging from poverty, gender equality and the empowerment of women
to good governance and private sector development.
</P>
<P>
At the end of July 1998, approvals of UNDP Africa projects
amounted to 764 million U.S. dollars out of total authorized
programming of 976 million U.S. dollars for the 1997-2000 period.
</P>
<P>
UNDP's renewed emphasis on empowerment of African people has
become necessary because past approaches have failed to eradicate
poverty on the continent.
</P>
<P>
Faced with the fact that Africa is the only continent where
poverty is predicted to increase in the 21st century, Awori
stressed that UNDP Africa Bureau must turn to those who know
development best and who will ultimately reap the rewards of its
success or pay the price of failure -- African themselves.
</P>
<P>
UNDP will seek to forge new development partnerships with
African youth, traditional leaders, churches and other religious
groups. "We must integrate ourselves into the rich networks of
existing grass-roots and community-based organizations," she said.
</P>
<P>
UNDP is now looking at ways in which it can work with African
religious leaders, to draw on the wealth of experience that they
have acquired. "We can learn a lot from them," she said.
</P>
<P>
Facing up to the consequences of the declining trend of
official development assistance (ODA), UNDP has identified the
negative trend as among Africa's most critical challenges.
</P>
<P>
Accounting for the lion's share of external resource flows to
Africa, ODA fell from 14.2 billion U.S. dollars in 1992 to 12.8
billion U.S. dollars in 1996. ODA flows have fallen for short of
the 30 billion U.S. dollars a year that some economists estimate
is needed to reduce poverty in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Although the General Assembly set an ODA target of 0.7 percent
of GNP for donor countries in 1996, these countries on average
provided ODA equivalent to just 0.25 percent of GDP.
</P>
<P>
"Declining ODA is a reality and I think it is important that
Africans wake up to that reality," Awori said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990428.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 16:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Algerian President-Elect Sworn In </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALGIERS, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Algerian President-elect
Abdelaziz Bouteflika was sworn in Tuesday for a five-year term
according to the Algerian constitution.
</P>
<P>
In the inaugural speech, Bouteflika spoke highly of the efforts
made by outgoing President Liamine Zeroual in safeguarding the
national order since he came to power in 1995, the Algerian News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Efforts to achieve public peace and eradicate violence in
thoughts, words or actions will take priority in the new
government's work, Bouteflika said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the responsibility of the state to preserve the
security of individuals and properties.
</P>
<P>
The state should mobilize all ranks to stop violence and
eliminate its effects in line with the laws of the republic, he
said.
</P>
<P>
It is also responsible for stamping out all direct and
indirect causes of rampant vicious acts of violence, he added.
</P>
<P>
He urged all sides concerned to work together to stabilize the
situation in the country.
</P>
<P>
Algeria has been rebuilding its institutions since 1992 when
the authority canceled parliamentary elections the now-banned
Islamic Salvation Front was poised to win. The move triggered an
Islamic insurgency that has left some 75,000 people dead.
</P>
<P>
The presidential election on April 15 had been originally seen
by the vast array of opposition parties as a chance to break with
the old order of military-backed rule to help mend the nation
fractured by deeply rooted division and the insurgency.
</P>
<P>
But after six other candidates dropped out of the race in
protest of voting fraud, Bouteflika, who was widely seen as the
choice of the powerful military-backed establishment, became the
only contender and won 73.75 percent of the vote. 
</P>
</TEXT>
