<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: UNDP Works Hard to Promote African Development (2)  by Gu Zhenqiu and Ding Baozhong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOUSTON, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Another priority area for UNDP is
to capitalize on globalization's opportunities while responding to
its challenges.
</P>
<P>
In his September 1998 progress report on the implementation of
the U.N. New Agenda for the Development of Africa in the 1990s,
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan said that globalization offers
major economic and social benefits, such as access to large
financial savings, new export markets and new technologies.
</P>
<P>
But in the case of Africa, he pointed out that globalization,
in the short term, has led to a significant marginalization of the
continent, largely because African exports are mainly primary
products, with little progress made in diversifying into
manufactureed goods.
</P>
<P>
Africa's export revenues have grown only marginally, due to
price uncertainties associated with commodities and the negative
impact of higher interest rates on export financing. In addition,
the U.N. chief said that Africa faces the risk of further
marginalization if it fails to attract more foreign capital.
</P>
<P>
UNDP, since its meeting held early this year in Benin, has
realized that efforts must be made to support African countries by
helping them to develop and implement adaptive strategies to
minimize the adverse fallout from globalization and take advantage
of the opportunities.
</P>
<P>
Africa's debt burden is a third priority area for UNDP Africa
Bureau. External public debt reached 223 billion U.S. dollars in
1997 and the Heavily Indebted Poor Countries (HIPC) initiative,
established in 1996 to reduce the debt burden, has been largely
ineffective.
</P>
<P>
"We would like to see Africa move into the new millenium with
no debt," she said.
</P>
<P>
The fourth priority area is a redoubling of UNDP's commitment
to serve as a voice for the poorest of the poor and other
marginalized groups, including women and those affected by
HIV/AIDS, the killing disease in the world at large.
</P>
<P>
UNDP already has been doing a lot of work with women, for which
it allocates 20 percent of its funds. "It is important that women
know this," she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990428.0040 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan to Provide Sao Tome With Food Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Japan has decided to provide Sao
Tome and Principe with food aid worth one million U.S. dollars,
the Angolan News Agency Angop reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to an agreement signed by the two governments Monday,
Japan will continue to provide more rice to the tiny Atlantic
island country. Sao Tome has been receiving food aid from Japan
for 17 years.
</P>
<P>
The agreement demands that the money gained through selling the
aid food should be used in implementing the poverty elimination
program.
</P>
<P>
At the signing ceremony, Japanese Ambassador Hideki Saski
called on the government of Huilherme Posser da Costa to show
transparency in using the Japanese assistance so that Japan would
increase its aid to the island country.
</P>
<P>
Saski noted his government has been watching the flow of its
assistance since 1995 and it hopes that the food aid could go
directly to the poorest.
</P>
<P>
Sao Tome and Principe is one of the least developed countries
identified by the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Rice and banana are the basic food for the local citizens. But
a serious shortage of rice has made the rice price shoot up in the
market, much higher than those of banana and cassava. 
</P>
</TEXT>
