<HEADLINE> U.S. Backs Infrastructure Development Program in Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOUSTON, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The United States on Tuesday
morning announced its plan to support the infrastructure program
in Africa in a bid to help the Sub-Saharan region boost economic
growth and better life quality for the population of more than 700
million.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to some 750 representatives of businesses and
governments in both Africa and the United States, Rodney Slater,
U.S. transportation secretary, said that "Our initiative seeks to
create new opportunities and a higher quality of life for the
ordinary citizens in both Africa and America by improving the
basic transportation infrastructure of Africa."
</P>
<P>
"Improved transportation within, to and from this major new
market will allow economies on both sides of the Atlantic to move
to higher heights than ever before," he said.
</P>
<P>
Transportation is a major component of the U.S. Government's
partnership with Africa and the U.S. Department of Transportation
has launched a major initiative to support the Partnership, he
said.
</P>
<P>
"The theme of our initiative is 'Transportation: the Tie that
Binds.' Transportation is about more than concrete, asphalt and
steel -- it is about connecting people to people," he said, adding
that the United States will help Africa in three ways.
</P>
<P>
"First, we seek to help Africa compete more effectively in the
global marketplace by showing how governments can adjust economic
policies to allow market forces greater flexibility," Slater said.
</P>
<P>
"Second, we seek to expand trade and investment opportunities
for U.S. investors who want to bring transportation technology and
transportation-related goods and services to African markets," he
said. "The bottom line is that if you can't get there, you can't
trade."
</P>
<P>
"Third, we seek to foster economic development in Africa
through training, technical assistance and improved transportation
services for local communities," he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. transportation secretary made the remarks at the
five-day "Attracting Capital to Africa Summit," which began here
on Saturday last week.
</P>
<P>
The biannual conference follows on the heals of the U.S.-Africa
Ministerial Meetings held in Washington last month, both
gatherings are seen as an integral part of the redefinition of the
U.S. relationship with Africa. The first such summit was held in
April in Virginia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
