<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Signs Call-Up Order for Expanded Bombing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 27 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton Tuesday
signed a call-up order to have 33,102 reservists to active duty to
support NATO's ever-expanding bombing against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
He announced that about 2,000 members of the Air National Guard
and Air Force reserve in eight states will be the first to be
mobilized.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said he signed the order under the request of Defense
Secretary William Cohen who intended to use the call-up authority
to immediately activate 2,100 airmen to support the continued NATO
airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
It would be the biggest activation of such troops since 239,000
reservists were called to duty during the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
It also marked the first non-voluntary call-up of reservists
since the NATO airstrikes began on March 24.
</P>
<P>
"These reserves are essential to America's military strength;
they are part of the total force we bring to bear whenever our men
and women in uniform are called to action," Clinton said. It was
not immediately known how many of the reservists would operate in
the Balkans and how many would work at bases elsewhere in Europe
and in the United States.
</P>
<P>
Cohen told a Pentagon news conference earlier Tuesday that the
call-up would be made in stages, reflecting the needs of U.S. Army
Gen. Wesley Clark, the top NATO commander, who is expanding allied
air operations.
</P>
<P>
Cohen also said NATO would continue to insist that an armed
international force be allowed to enforce any peace deal in Kosovo
and that it be led by NATO rather than troops under the United
Nations flag.
</P>
<P>
About three-quarters of the total are expected to be Air Force
reserves. Some Army National Guard and Reserve members are likely
to be called up to support the Apache helicopter operations in
Albania. A smaller number of Navy and Marine Corps reservists also
are likely to get the call to help with port management, U.S.
officials said.
</P>
<P>
Under U.S. law, Clinton can authorize what it termed a
"Presidential Selected Reserve Call-up," which would authorize the
defense secretary to select from a pool of as many as 200,000
reserve or National Guard troops.
</P>
<P>
Those called up would be subject to serve on active duty for as
long as 270 days if needed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
