<HEADLINE> China Calls For Joint Efforts to Resolve Financial Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 27 (Xinhua) -- China called here Tuesday for
joint efforts of the international community to resolve financial
crisis.
</P>
<P>
"With increased economic globalization and financial
integration, and growing interdependence among different
economies, the ultimate resolution of crisis depends on the joint
efforts of the international community," said Liu Mingkang, Deputy
Governor of People's Bank of China.
</P>
<P>
Liu made the remarks at the 52nd meeting of the Interim
Committee of the Board of Governors on the International Monetary
Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
Liu said although the risk of global recession has been
reduced, the world economic outlook is still less than optimistic.
"The global slowdown may yet prove deeper and more prolonged than
so far assumed."
</P>
<P>
World economic prospects will mainly rely on the ability of the
United States to achieve a "soft landing", a solid recovery of the
Japanese economy, a strengthened domestic demand to maintain a
sustained growth in Europe, a substantial revival of capital flow
to emerging market economies, and the stability of the major
exchange rates, he added.
</P>
<P>
Calling on the advanced economies to undertake the
responsibility of supporting the Asian economic recovery, Liu said
they should coordinate their macroeconomic policies and maintain
economic growth to contribute to economic recovery in the crisis
countries and promote world economic growth.
</P>
<P>
On the Chinese economy, Liu said in 1999, the Chinese
government will continue to pursue a vigorous fiscal policy and
sound monetary policy to stimulate domestic demand and achieve the
growth target of 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
"We are confident about continuing to maintain strong growth
and the stability of the renminbi in the context of an unfavorable
external environment," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed his belief that with the mainland of China's
expected robust economic growth in 1999 and Hong Kong's remarkable
flexibility to adjust, the economy of Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region will recover in the second half of 1999.
</P>
<P>
As for the reform of the international monetary and financial
system, Liu said such reform is critical to guarantee exchange
rate stability and the effective supervision of capital flows.
</P>
<P>
"The start and spread of the recent financial crisis reflects
the weakness and difficulties facing the current international
financial system which has seen fundamental changes take place in
its international economic structure over the past 50 years," he
said.
</P>
<P>
While continuing to play the central role in international
monetary and financial issues, the IMF should give greater
consideration to the specific political, economic, and social
conditions of its members, and more flexibility should be allowed
in its policy advice, liu said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
