<HEADLINE> Israel "on Verge" of Buying U.S. Fighter Jets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Israel will soon decide what
kind of U.S. fighter jets it would buy -- either F-15s, or F-16s,
or a mix -- in a new package offered by Washington last year,
Israel's Defense Minister Moshe Arens said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli defense minister, at a joint news conference with
U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen after their talks at the
Pentagon, said Israel was "on the verge of making a decision" on
the fighter jets.
</P>
<P>
Cohen told the joint news conference that he and Arens
"discussed Israel's military modernization program and the United
States's commitment to help them to maintain their qualitative
edge in defense."
</P>
<P>
Cohen said there also was a "need to support Jordan's security"
because of the key role Amman plays in regional stability.
</P>
<P>
Last September, Washington announced it had offered to sell 30
F-15 and 60 F-16 fighter jets to Israel for an estimated 2.5
billion dollars for each package. The advanced F-15I ground attack
jets are built by Boeing Co. and the F-16C and F-16D models by
Lockheed Martin. Arens is leaving to visit a Boeing Co. plant
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Israel also asked the United States early last year to expand
the Arrow anti-missile defense program to three batteries from
two. Arrow is an Israeli-produced missile jointly funded by
Washington.
</P>
<P>
As a response, Cohen said at the joint news conference that the
Clinton administration supported the continuation of the
development of a third battery and would work on 40 million
dollars in funding for the program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
