<HEADLINE> Algerian President Rejects PM's Resignation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALGIERS, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Algerian President Abdelaziz
Bouteflika Tuesday rejected the resignation of sitting Prime
Minister Ismail Hamdani and asked him to stay.
</P>
<P>
Hamdani tendered his resignation shortly after Bouteflika was
sworn in as president earlier in the day, the Algerian News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Former President Liamine Zerowal appointed Hamdani prime
minister in December 1998.
</P>
<P>
On April 16, a day after the presidential election, Bouteflika,
who won a landslide victory, said the current government led by
Hamdani will continue its mission through the summit of the
Organization of African Unity, which is due to be held in Algeria
in July.
</P>
<P>
Algeria has been rebuilding its institutions since 1992 when
the authority canceled parliamentary elections the now-banned
Islamic Salvation Front was poised to win. The move triggered an
Islamic insurgency that has left some 75,000 people dead.
</P>
<P>
The presidential election on April 15 had been originally seen
by the vast array of opposition parties as a chance to break with
the old order of military-backed rule to help mend the nation
fractured by deeply rooted division and the insurgency.
</P>
<P>
But after six other candidates dropped out of the race in
protest of voting fraud, Bouteflika, who was widely seen as the
choice of the powerful military-backed establishment, became the
only contender and won 73.75 percent of the vote. 
</P>
</TEXT>
