<HEADLINE> Angolan PM Post Controversial Prior to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Major controversy has arisen
during debate in Angolan parliament prior to the constitutional
amendment on whether to keep the post of prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Bornito de Sousa, vice chairman of the Constitution Committee
of Angola' s National Assembly, said here Tuesday that the ruling
People's Movement for the Liberation of Angola (MPLA) insists that
the president to act as prime minister, whereas some other parties
request to retain the post of prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Angolan President Eduardo dos Santos reshuffled the cabinet on
January 30 with an excuse to downsize the institutions, and the
prime minister position is taken over by the president himself.
</P>
<P>
The president's decision has yet to be confirmed by the
constitution. Angola's National Assembly will amend the
constitution this year. The ruling MPLA takes up 129 seats of the
223 seats in the parliament, while the break-away UNITA Renovation
Committee have 70, the rest belongs to other 10 parties.
</P>
<P>
It is widely speculated that draft the amendment on
strengthening presidential power might be adopted.
</P>
<P>
Sousa said to date, all parties have handed in their drafts of
amendment with most members of parliament are for the country to
be a united one under decentralized administration, but still some
others insist on federation.
</P>
<P>
However, he admitted that in areas of "citizens' basic rights
and freedom", opinions contained in draft amendment handed in by
various parties are quite close.
</P>
<P>
Most parties agree to keep the parliamentary system and on the
establishment of a market economy based on public, private and
cooperate ownership. 
</P>
</TEXT>
