<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: African Leaders, U.S. Firms Discuss Investment  on Oil, Energy  ( by Gu Zhenqiu and Ding Baozhong) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOUSTON, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The "Attracting Capital to Africa
Summit" concluded here Wednesday with strong African appeals for
more U.S. investment on the continent, rich in natural and human
resources.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, some cabinet members of the Clinton administration,
who attended the summit, said that promoting trade and investment
in Africa is also beneficial to the United States.
</P>
<P>
Gabon already gets 80 percent of its export revenues from oil,
but the African country would like more, with the help of major
oil companies, President Omar Bongo of Gabon has said.
</P>
<P>
Like other presidents and national officials from African
countries, Bongo is touting his nation as a good place to invest.
The president is at Houston to attend the five-day gathering aimed
at exploring opportunities for the two-way trade and investment
between Africa and the United States.
</P>
<P>
In addition to proven oil reserves, which Gabon has doubled
since 1996, Africa offers vast and untapped resources of natural
gas, Bongo said in a speech to some 750 business and government
representatives from both Africa and the United States.
</P>
<P>
"I assure you, you will be able to double your returns," Bongo
said.
</P>
<P>
In response, William Richardson, U.S. secretary of energy, said
in a prepared speech that "the future of the U.S. investment in
Africa will be mainly in the field of energy."
</P>
<P>
"Doing business with Africa creates American jobs," Richardson
said.
</P>
<P>
Ghanaian President Jerry Rawlings said that it is time now for
Africa and its friends to counter negative perceptions. The
continent boasted 5 percent economic growth last year, when many
parts of the world were struggling in the wake of the Asian
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Also at the discussion in the forms of workshops and roundtable
consultations were some U.S. company executives, who outlined the
difficulties in investing in Africa.
</P>
<P>
In the case of oil and gas, Africa is at disadvantage because
much of its considerable resources are high-cost, technically
challenging and in remote locations, said Ken Evans, vice
president of Exxon, a world-famous oil company in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
Because oil companies have such long lead times, sanctity of
agreements is of prime importance, he said.
</P>
<P>
In order to invest its money, business needs civil order,
economic and political stability, anti-corruption standards by
government and a reliable infrastructure in the African countries,
Evans said.
</P>
<P>
Despite such difficulties, Chevron Vice Chairman David O'Reilly
said the company and its partners have invested 9 billion U.S.
dollars in Africa during the past five years, and will invest 12
billion U.S. dollars there in the next five years.
</P>
<P>
Rodney Slater, secretary of Transportation, said that the
United States plans to help Africa improve its transportation
infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
"We seek to expand trade and investment opportunities for U.S.
investors who want to bring transportation technology and
transportation-related goods and services to African market," he
said, "The bottom line is that if you can't get there, you can't
trade."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990428.0060 </DOCNO>
