<DOCNO> XIE19990428.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Five Major Exhibition Halls for Horti-Expo '99 (6) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The '99 International
Horticultural Exposition is scheduled to open in Kunming, capital
of southwest China's Yunnan Province, on May 1. Following is a
brief introduction to the five major exhibition halls at the venue
of the exposition:
</P>
<P>
The indoor exhibition area for the '99 International
Horticultural Exposition consists of five exhibition halls, namely
the China Hall, the Human and Nature Hall, the Grand Greenhouse,
the Science and Technology Hall and the International Hall.
</P>
<P>
Covering an area of 33,000 sq m and with a total floor space of
16,800 sq m, the China Hall ranks first among the five major
exhibition halls in terms of architectural functions. It has
adopted the traditional Chinese garden design, with three
courtyards interconnected by corridors. There are ponds, rockeries,
small bridges, weird stones and pretty flowers and trees in the
courtyards. The theme of the China Hall is "Splendid Gardens and
Gardening Art of China". It has provided all provinces and regions
across China with a chance to display their time-honored history
of horticulture and distinct gardening arts.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 5,000 sq m in floor space, the Human and Nature Hall is
shaped like a trefoil. With "Man and Nature" as its theme, the
hall is divided into three sub-halls, namely the hall of indoor
ornamental plants, the "mankind and global ecology" hall and the
hall of vegetables, medicinal herb and traditional Chinese
medicine.
</P>
<P>
Reputed as a small "kingdom of plants", the Grand Greenhouse is
divided into three parts, devoted, respectively, to flowers,
tropical plants and Alpine plants, with four separate exhibition
zones displaying tropical rain forest, temperate zone plants, sub-
tropical plants and Alpine plants respectively. There are also a
large number of rare and precious plants and gardening
masterpieces from all over the world in the greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
Covering an area of more than 6,000 sq m, the Science and
Technology Hall, which seems like a combination of geometric
figures in its external shape, is intended to present the theme of
"Horticulture and Science and Technology". On display in the hall
are the latest scientific and technological achievements in the
field of horticulture worldwide. There is also a large ball-shape
cineorama in front of the hall.
</P>
<P>
With a height of 21 meters, the International Hall is mainly
devoted to masterpieces of horticultural works from all over the
world. Designers of this structure said that it symbolizes
equality, unity and harmony among peoples across the world in
their march toward the 21st century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990428.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak, Turkmenistan, Afghanistan to Discuss Gas Pipeline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan, Turkmenistan and
Afghanistan will open talks on a proposed 2 billion U.S. dollar
gas pipeline project here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Turkmenistan's Deputy Prime Minister Batyr Sardaev and Taliban
official for mines and industries Ahmed Jan have arrived here for
the talks, official sources told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Chaudhry Nisar Ali Khan, minister for petroleum and natural
resources, will lead the Pakistani delegation in the talks.
</P>
<P>
The planned 1,280-kilometer gas pipeline will carry gas to
Pakistan from Turkmenistan via Afghanistan. It will connect the
Dauletabad gas field in southeastern Turkmenistan with Multan in
Pakistan's Punjab Province.
</P>
<P>
The gas pipeline, which will be 48 inches in diameter, is
planned to carry 20 billion cubic meters of gas every year.
</P>
<P>
The proposed pipeline, the first major economic investment in
Afghanistan in the last two decades, will run through the west and
south of the country which is now under the Taliban's control.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan and Turkmenistan are very interested in the early
construction of the project. However, instability in war-torn
Afghanistan is believed to be the main hurdle to the project.
</P>
<P>
Turkmenistan is the only country which has sent its foreign
minister to the Taliban's stronghold of Kandahar, the second
largest city in Afghanistan, for talks with the Taliban's supreme
leader, Mullah Omar. It also hosted the face-to-face talks between
the Taliban and their rival, the Northern Alliance, in Ashgabat in
March this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990428.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
