<HEADLINE> ESCAP Session Ends in Thailand With Call for Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Economic and Social
Commission for Asia and the Pacific (ESCAP) ended the 55th Session
here Wednesday with a call for reform and regional cooperation to
realize comprehensive economic and social recovery.
</P>
<P>
Members of the U.N. body unanimously adopted the report of the
session which contains resolutions calling for greater economic
and financial monitoring and surveillance in the region.
</P>
<P>
The report also highlights sustained development of inland
water transport, involvement of older persons in the work of the
United Nations and national socioeconomic programs and closer
regional cooperation in tackling the Y2K problem.
</P>
<P>
In her closing statement, Nyam-Osoryn Tuya, chairperson of the
session, urged governments in the region to sustain efforts and
speed up reforms toward economic recovery and enhance
international and regional initiatives for revamping global
economic frameworks.
</P>
<P>
"Considering that the Asian crisis was not the first one in the
last few years and that it may not be the last in the coming
years, countries are encouraged to fully participate in the
formulation of a new international financial system," she said.
</P>
<P>
She also emphasized the need for growth with equity, saying the
liberalization process has to be managed carefully by countries in
line with the conditions of domestic institutions, level of human
resources development and economic governance.
</P>
<P>
The 55th Session of ESCAP began last Thursday with the Senior
Officials' Segment, followed by the Ministerial Meeting, which was
opened Monday.
</P>
<P>
The theme chosen for this year's session was "Asia and the
Pacific Into the Twenty-First Century: Information Technology,
Globalization, Economic Security and Development." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
