<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1500 GMT, April 28 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- Thousands of files of the Indian Home Ministry
were destroyed in a big fire which broke out in Jaisalmer House
near India Gate here Wednesday, fire brigade sources said.
</P>
<P>
The fire occurred in the afternoon and destroyed the single-
story record room of the Home Ministry within minutes. Thousands
of records concerning payment of pensions to freedom fighters were
destroyed in the fire, the Press Trust of India (PTI) quoted some
employees of the ministry as saying.
</P>
<P>
The fire was brought under control within an hour by 15 fire
tenders. The cause of the fire is yet to be known. (India-Fire-
Records)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- A committee chaired by a British Member of Parliament
said on Wednesday that the latest massacre by NATO of civilians in
Yugoslavia confirmed that NATO is breaching the Geneva Convention.
</P>
<P>
The Committee for Peace in the Balkans, chaired by Alice Mahon,
a member in the House of Commons, said in a statement that a NATO
guided weapon on Tuesday massacred between 20 and 40 civilians,
including at least 11 children, when it hit a residential area.
</P>
<P>
The committee called for those responsible for the crimes,
whether they be military commanders or politicians, to be brought
to justice. (Britain-MPs-NATO)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MADRID -- Spanish Foreign Minister Abel Matutes Y Juan said here
on Wednesday that the Spanish Government believes that Russia's
recent mediation may help speed up the ending of the Kosovo crisis
in a diplomatic way.
</P>
<P>
Matutes said that after three rounds of talks with his Russian
counterpart Igor Ivanov, he was convinced of Russia's "very active
attitude" toward the resolution of the Kosovo crisis, adding that
Russia's recent diplomatic efforts have brought hope to ending the
Kosovo crisis by political and diplomatic means.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that peace could come soon when bloodshed and
suffering would end in Yugoslavia. (Spain-Russia-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BUCHAREST -- An earthquake measuring 5.5 on the open-ended
Richter scale hit eastern Romania on Wednesday, but so far there
has been no official report of casualties.
</P>
<P>
The quake, the strongest in the country since 1990, occurred at
11:47 local time (09:47 GMT) and lasted five seconds, with its
epicenter located in the region of Vrancea, according to the
Romanian Institute of Geophysics.
</P>
<P>
The tremor was felt throughout the country. (Romania-
Earthquake)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has
warned Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat not to declare an
independent Palestinian State on May 4 this year.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said the peace process could be moved forward if
Arafat refrains from doing so, otherwise, the 1993 Oslo accords
could collapse and he would not further implement the Oslo accords
if he wins in the May 17 elections.
</P>
<P>
The PLO is discussing in Gaza whether to declare statehood on
May 4.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu opposes unilateral Palestinian statehood declaration,
threatening to annex parts of the West Bank now under Israeli
control. The peace process could only be moved forward through
negotiations, he said, adding that no unilateral actions could
help.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he said that Israel could not accept the resolution
adopted by the United Nations Human Rights Commission Tuesday in
Geneva, which calls for Palestinian self-determination on the
basis of the U.N. partition resolution 181 adopted in 1947.
</P>
<P>
The commission's resolution also calls for the right of
Palestinian refugees to return home. (Israel-Netanyahu-Palestine )
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin on Wednesday signed
11 agreements with visiting Belarussian President Alexander
Lukashenko to deepen bilateral cooperation.
</P>
<P>
According to the local news media, the agreements included
documents concerning the formation of a single customs space,
border policy, a joint security concept and defense cooperation,
mainly in the field of arms production.
</P>
<P>
Lukashenko, who arrived here on April 27, made a two-day visit
to Moscow and discussed the Kosovo war with the Russian side. (
Yeltsin-Lukashenko-Agreements) 
</P>
