<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia's Attitude Turns Tough on Border Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopian Prime Minister
Meles Zenawi reiterated Ethiopia's position that Eritrea needs to
officially declare that it will withdraw its troops from "all
Ethiopian land and agree to set a short time frame for the
withdrawal".
</P>
<P>
Meles made the remarks when meeting with U.N. Special Envoy for
Africa Mohammed Sahnoun here Wednesday, the office of Ethiopian
Government Spokesperson Selome Taddesse said in a statement here.
</P>
<P>
Sahnoun is currently touring the Horn of Africa, aiming at
ending the 11- month conflict between Ethiopia and Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
The statement accused Eritrea of invading Ethiopia's land,
saying, "Noting that Eritrea invaded Ethiopia's sovereign
territory in May 1998, Meles emphasized the importance of undoing
the invasion before other matters can be contemplated."
</P>
<P>
"As long as Ethiopian territory remains under Eritrean
occupation, it is impossible to discuss a cease-fire and negotiate
a resolution to the border conflict," the Ethiopian Premier was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Sahnoun told Meles that he will continue with his efforts, said
the statement.
</P>
<P>
Sahnoun arrived here Tuesday after holding talks in Asmara with
Eritrean leaders Monday.
</P>
<P>
Both Ethiopia and Eritrea have nominally accepted the peace
plan proposed by the Organization of African Unity (OAU), but so
far no cease- fire has been agreed.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia accepted the OAU framework agreement last November
while Eritrea accepted it in February this year.
</P>
<P>
The 11-month border conflict escalated into fierce fighting in
June 1998 and in February and March this year.
</P>
<P>
Sahnoun's last visit to the Horn of African was in early
February this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
