<HEADLINE> U.N. Urged to Play Positive Role in Solving Kosovo Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign Minister Igor
Ivanov said Wednesday that Russia and Greece both support the
United Nations to play a positive role in the political settlement
of the current Balkan conflict.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov made the remark at a joint press conference after a
meeting with his Greek counterpart George Papandreou,who arrived
here on a working visit to Russia.
</P>
<P>
He said that their meeting focused on the present situation in
the Balkan region, saying both countries agreed to set up a
special working team for providing aid to Kosovo refugees.
</P>
<P>
On the latest U.S. announcement of sending reserves to the
Balkan region, Ivanov said that Russia is opposed to any action
that might make the situation there more complicated, including
oil embargo and ground offensive.
</P>
<P>
These actions will cause heavy casualties on both sides, he
warned.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Papandreou said that such actions "should not
happen," adding that the damage NATO has inflicted to the region
could not be healed within the coming decade.
</P>
<P>
He complained that NATO's military action in the region has
brought serious economic loss to Greece which has a big investment
in Yugoslavia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
