<DOCNO> XIE19990428.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Orders for U.S. Durable Goods Up 2 Percent in March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Orders to U.S. factories for
big-ticket durable goods from refrigerators to tanks rose 2
percent to a seasonally adjusted 197.7 billion U.S. dollars in
March, with improvement showing in most sectors, the Commerce
Department reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The increase followed a much bigger decline in demand for
durable goods in February, although revised figures pegged that
drop at 3.9 percent, not as bad as the 5.0 percent decline first
estimated.
</P>
<P>
Economists had predicted a modest rebound in March. However,
many analysts remain concerned about signs of weakness in U.S.
industry.
</P>
<P>
American manufacturers have been hurt by world economic
troubles that began in Asia nearly two years ago. Export sales
have plummeted, and low-priced imports have increased competition
for consumers' attention here.
</P>
<P>
The recovery in durable-goods orders in March was led by the
military industry, which saw a 36.2 percent jump in new orders.
Excluding defense items, orders for all other goods rose 1 percent
for the month.
</P>
<P>
Transportation orders rose 3.6 percent in March after a large,
12.8 percent drop in February that was somewhat skewed by a
downward swing in demand for aircraft.
</P>
<P>
March orders for electronic and other electrical equipment rose
3.1 percent, and for industrial machinery and equipment, rose 2.9
percent.
</P>
<P>
The soft spot in March durable-goods orders was primary metals,
where demand fell 1.4 percent after a wild upward swing of 7.3
percent in February. The steel industry, which falls into this
sector, has been among the hardest hit by economic hard times
abroad and is seeking government protection from low-priced
imports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
