<HEADLINE> Pakistan Proposes Multi-Ethnic Govt. in Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan Wednesday proposed
establishing a representative multi-ethnic government through an
indigenous process in Afghanistan to realize durable peace and
stability.
</P>
<P>
The proposal was made by Illahi Bukhsh Soomro, speaker of
Pakistan's National Assembly, at a banquet he hosted in honor of
the visiting Chairman Gennady Seleznev of the State Duma (lower
house) of the Russian Federation.
</P>
<P>
"The Afghanistan tragedy is a source of great concern to us.
For the last 20 years Pakistan has exerted all possible efforts,
individually and together with other countries, for the
restoration of durable peace and stability in that country,"
Soomro noted.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that this can best be achieved on the basis of a
representative multi-ethnic government through an indigenous
process," he said.
</P>
<P>
Soomro stressed that "the return of peace and normalcy in
Afghanistan will not only be in the interest of the people of
Afghanistan but of the entire region."
</P>
<P>
"It will also create new opportunities for cooperation between
Pakistan and Russia. We as parliamentarians can join hands in
achieving this common goal," Soomro added.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of Kashmir, Soomro expressed his hope that Russia
as a world power will play its due role in promoting an amicable
settlement of the issue and preventing an arms race in the region.
</P>
<P>
"Without a settlement of the Kashmir issue there cannot be full
normalization of relations between India and Pakistan and the
threat of conflict will continue to cast dark shadows on the
region," the speaker stressed.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan, as a developing country, wants to devote its
resources to the well-being and prosperity of its people, said
Soomro. "It seeks to achieve normal, friendly and cooperative
relations with all its neighbors."
</P>
<P>
Soomro said Pakistan is also keen to avert a nuclear arms race
in the region.
</P>
<P>
"Pakistan attaches great importance to its relations with the
Russian Federation," he said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his confidence that Seleznev's visit to Pakistan
will not only help promote relations between the two parliaments
but also between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Soomro said Seleznev's visit, less than a week after Prime
Minister Nawaz Sharif's trip to Russia, "is indicative of the
mutual desire of our governments and peoples to overcome the
distrust and differences of the past and lay down the foundation
of a new edifice of friendly and cooperative relations."
</P>
<P>
He also said Seleznev's visit will greatly help promote mutual
trust and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Seleznev, accompanied by a 49-member entourage, arrived here
earlier Wednesday on a three-day visit at the invitation of
Soomro. Apart from the capital city, the Russian delegation will
also tour Lahore, Pakistan's second largest city and the
provincial capital of Punjab. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
