<DOCNO> XIE19990428.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cambodia Adopts Law on Banning Land Mines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The Cambodian National
Assembly Wednesday adopted a law to ban the use of land mines.
</P>
<P>
Under the law, no one is allowed to use any kind of
anti-personnel land mines under any circumstances except for
training purposes.
</P>
<P>
"And the user will be imprisoned from 10 to 20 years and will
be fined in cash from 10 million riel (about 2,600 U.S. dollars)
to 20 million riel (about 5,200 dollars)," the law states. In
addition, those who used land mines and killed people will be
punished by law.
</P>
<P>
Ieng Mouly, president of the Cambodian Mines Action Center
(CMAC), told reporters that "the law is of great significance for
the entire Cambodian people and it will help greatly reduce the
loss of lives and property."
</P>
<P>
Ieng Mouly said, "365,000 hectares of land in Cambodia were
minefields and so far, only 6,000 hectares have been cleared of
mines."
</P>
<P>
Land mines have already killed more than 13,000 people and
disabled 100,000 others in the country.
</P>
<P>
"Thanks to the efforts of the government and the CMAC, the
number of accidents relating to land mines has dropped to 50 from
150 per month in the last two years, well down from 600 a month in
1992," Ieng Mouly added.
</P>
<P>
Cambodia signed the Ottawa Treaty against the use, stockpiling,
production and transfer of anti-personnel mines in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990428.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 13:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Protest Against U.N. Resolution on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli Foreign Ministry
has lodged a protest against a resolution adopted by the United
Nations Human Rights Commission, which supports Palestinian
self-determination on the basis of the U.N. partition resolution
181 adopted in 1947.
</P>
<P>
With European support, the commission adopted on Tuesday in
Geneva the resolution on the Palestinian issue, which also calls
for the right of Palestinian refugees to return home.
</P>
<P>
Israel's lobbying efforts to prevent the Geneva voting failed,
and the United States was the only country among the 53 attendance
that voted against the resolution.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli Foreign Ministry issued a statement Tuesday night
blasting the resolution and expressing particular disappointment
at the European support.
</P>
<P>
Such a move "distances Europe from involvement it could have in
the peace process," the statement warned.
</P>
<P>
The ministry sent a strong protest to the U.N. on Wednesday,
criticizing the commission for passing the resolution without
mentioning the foundation of the peace process set in the
U.N. Security Council resolutions 242 and 338.
</P>
<P>
According to Israel's version of explanation, the two
resolutions entitle Israel not to return all its occupied Arab
territories while at the same time urge its Arab neighbors to
recognize Israel's security. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
