<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cambodia's Entry Will Boost Solidarity: ASEAN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Secretary General of the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) Rodolfo C. Severino
said Wednesday that he believes Cambodia's entry into the regional
grouping will strengthen its solidarity.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Xinhua News Agency here, Severino said the
membership of Cambodia would increase the diversity of ASEAN and
would even influence the consensus process, understanding and
positions of the grouping.
</P>
<P>
Severino acknowledged that with more countries joining ASEAN,
the organization will have more difficulty in reaching consensus.
</P>
<P>
"But despite the difficulties, we need Southeast Asian
solidarity, cooperation and integration," he said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that Southeast Asian nations have more need to come
together to face the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
"In this globalization era, one nation, no matter how rich or
big, can no longer survive alone. Globalization leaves ASEAN no
other choice but to stick together," he said.
</P>
<P>
A ceremony will be held in Hanoi, Vietnam, on Friday to admit
Cambodia, finally fulfilling the ASEAN dream of including all the
10 countries in the region.
</P>
<P>
Cambodia was originally supposed to join ASEAN in July 1997.
But its membership was put on hold when a bitter political feud
between the then Co-Prime Ministers Hun Sen and Prince Norodom
Ranariddh burst into the open that month.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN, founded in 1967, currently groups Brunei, Indonesia,
Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and
Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
Severino pointed out that ASEAN has many dialogue partners.
</P>
<P>
"To have ASEAN's voice heard in the World Trade Organization
(WTO), the United Nations and dialogues with its partners, ASEAN
has to speak together, otherwise nobody will listen," he said.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN's dialogue partners include China, the United States,
Japan, the European Union, Canada, Australia, New Zealand, South
Korea, India and Russia.
</P>
<P>
On the China-ASEAN relations, Severino said ASEAN has good
relations with China.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN and China have many channels for holding talks, like the
foreign ministers meeting and senior officials meeting, the
secretary general said, adding that ASEAN also cooperates with
China in trade and investment and science and technology.
</P>
<P>
"ASEAN appreciates China's effort to uphold its currency, which
contributes much to the stability of the region," he said.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN supports China's early entry into WTO, which he said will
help the Sino-ASEAN trade relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990428.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
