<HEADLINE> Construction of Xi'an-Ankang Railway Underway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Workers started laying rails for
the 267-kilometer long Xi'an-Ankang Railway line in northwest
China's Shaanxi Province today, which is one of China's key
projects for the 1996-2000 period.
</P>
<P>
The railway, runs southward from Xi'an, capital of Shaanxi
Province and passes through the Qinling Range and Zhashui, Zhen'an
and Xunyang counties before reaching Ankang in the southern part
of the province.
</P>
<P>
The railway, which links Lanzhou-Lianyungang Railway in the
north and the Xiangfan-Chongqing Railway in the south, is
scheduled for completion on October 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
Local sources said that the railway line will help fulfill the
dreams of generations of local people and to promote economic
development along the route after completion. It has a capacity
for handling 20 million tons of cargo a year and eight passenger
trains each way every day.
</P>
<P>
The total investment of the railway is estimated at 9.85
billion yuan (about 1.2 billion U.S. dollars) and construction
began in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
