<DOCNO> XIE19990428.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Breaching Geneva Convention: British Committee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 28 (Xinhua) -- A committee chaired by a British
Member of Parliament said on Wednesday that the latest massacre by
NATO of civilians in Yugoslavia confirmed that NATO is breaching
the Geneva Convention.
</P>
<P>
The Committee for Peace in the Balkans, chaired by Alice Mahon,
a member in the House of Commons, said in a statement that a NATO
guided weapon on Tuesday massacred between 20 and 40 civilians,
including at least 11 children, when it hit a residential area.
</P>
<P>
The massacre confirmed again that "NATO is now routinely
violating the 1949 Geneva Convention which outlaws targeting of
civilians in war," the committee pointed out.
</P>
<P>
"The cornerstone of the 1949 Convention is the duty to protect
the life, health and safety of civilians and other non-combatants.
All warring parties have a duty to do everything possible to avoid
civilian targets and casualties," said the committee.
</P>
<P>
"Since NATO started bombing Yugoslavia, three times more
civilians may have been killed by NATO per day than the total
average daily deaths in the preceding year of civil war in Kosovo,
" the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"Under the Geneva Convention governing the conduct of war,
which is binding on all states, it is specifically stated that
'civilians shall not be the object of attack,' said the statement.
</P>
<P>
"By these criteria NATO has already committed numerous war
crimes in Yugoslavia including the deliberate and premeditated
decision to kill and maim civilians working in the Belgrade
television center on 23 April," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The committee called for those responsible for the crimes,
whether they be military commanders or politicians, to be brought
to justice.
</P>
<P>
The committee for Peace in Balkans was founded early this
decade to promote peace and reconciliation in the Balkan countries.
It strongly condemned NATO's airstrikes against Yugoslavia from
the very beginning.
</P>
<P>
A number of British MPs are working in the committee. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
