<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethnic Minority Donates Rare Trees to Horti-Expo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, April 28 (Xinhua) -- An ethnic minority in southwest
China's Yunnan Province has turned down an offer by a Japanese
tourist for buying a rare species of tree in large quantities for
10,000 yuan each and donated some of them to the '99 International
Horticultural Exposition instead.
</P>
<P>
The first world exposition to be held in a developing country,
the '99 horticulture show is scheduled to open in Kunming, capital
of Yunnan, on May 1 and last through October.
</P>
<P>
The trees, known as alexgeorgei or "Jishegougu" in Chinese,
were moved into the Tree Garden at the expo venue last summer from
the Gulu Township in the suburbs of Kunming, where people of the
Yi ethnic group, one of the 25 ethnic minorities in Yunnan, reside.
</P>
<P>
For generations the Yi people have planted such trees, whose
long and slim leaves look like chicken's tongues, around their
residences because the trees maintain exuberant leaves speckled
with little red fruit even in winter.
</P>
<P>
However, they had never actually realized the value of the tree
until early 1998, when a Japanese tourist, obviously well-versed
in botany, came to the town. Excited at first sight of the trees,
the Japanese asked the local people to sell him some of the trees
for 10,000 yuan (about 1,200 US dollars) each.
</P>
<P>
Though 10,000 yuan means an annual income of a local family,
the Yi people turned down the offer without hesitation. Meanwhile,
they immediately invited botanists from Kunming to give the tree a
full evaluation.
</P>
<P>
"We found that this tree is a species of the holly family never
reported before. Apart from ornamental value, the tree also has
significant economic value, as its fruit, leaves and bark can be
used to make medicine for treating rheumatoid arthritis," said
Jiang Zhixiang, one of the botanists who visited the Gulu Township.
</P>
<P>
According to Jiang, also chief advisor to the horticultural
show, the trees donated by the Yi people have all survived
transplantation, with new sprouts bursting out. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990428.0105 </DOCNO>
