<HEADLINE> Opening Ceremony of Horti-Expo Live On Internet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, April 28 (Xinhua) -- If you couldn't be in Kunming
when the '99 International Horticultural Exposition opens here
Friday evening, just start your computer at 8 p.m., access to the
Internet and there you may enjoy the entire opening ceremony
broadcast live.
</P>
<P>
"Don't miss the last grand international gathering of this
century," says an online advertisement presented by the Yunnan
Provincial Infoport, www.yn.cninfo.net, one of the service
providers for live broadcast.
</P>
<P>
The horticultural show in Kunming, capital of Yunnan Province,
is the first international exposition to be hosted by China, or by
a developing country.
</P>
<P>
It is also the first time for China to introduce on-line
broadcast of the opening ceremony of a major international
activity it hosts.
</P>
<P>
Some 7,000 professional and amateur performers will attend a
large entertainment show Friday evening after the horti-expo is
declared open. Journalists and Kunming citizens who have had the
chance to watch the rehearsals described the show, titled "A
romantic melody of heaven and earth", as very exciting and
inspiring.
</P>
<P>
The opening ceremony and performance will also be broadcast
live on www.expo99.net, a website opened on March 1 specially for
the upcoming expo. As the Chinese government's first attempt to
use the Internet for publicity of an international activity held
in China, the website has to date received more than 70,000 visits.
</P>
<P>
"Apart from the opening ceremony, we will plan to broadcast
live the inauguration of the expo venue scheduled at 8 a.m. on May
1, as well as some other major events during the six-month run of
the exposition," said Deng Hengyuan, one of the operators of the
expo website.
</P>
<P>
As China's several previous attempts of Internet broadcast,
including one by the China Central Television to broadcast its
1999 Chinese Lunar New Year entertainment soiree worldwide, have
unexpectedly encountered problems like communication jam and even
website breakdown, telecommunication departments in Yunnan have
spent big money on upgrading the facilities of both websites.
</P>
<P>
"Our website alone can accept one million visitors at a time,"
said Deng. 
</P>
</TEXT>
