<DOCNO> XIE19990428.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Int'l Relief Agency Provides Food to Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"We know that many families are really struggling now," said
Burk Oberle, WFP's country director for Somalia. "Their stocks are
either weak or dying; safe drinking water is in short supply, and
the region's entire economy is becoming more fragile by the day."
</P>
<P>
Puntland has been hit by drought since the end of last year.
Rains expected in December failed, and the region's main rain
season, which should have begun this month, is delayed.
</P>
<P>
U.N. agronomists predict that if rains are not received by
mid-May, thousands of head of livestock may die. This would
devastate the livelihood of over 100,000 nomadic pastoralists, who
are dependent on their animals as a direct food source.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey in Puntland by the U.N. Food Security
Assessment Unit (FSAU) , which works closely with WFP, indicates
that livestock milk production in the region is about one-fifth of
the normal amount for this time of year.
</P>
<P>
Pasture is considered to be very poor, and animals such as
sheep and goats are dying at unusually high rates due to the lack
of water.
</P>
<P>
Since November last year, WFP has been running a large
emergency operation in southern Somalia. So far WFP has
distributed over 11,500 tons of relief food in south Somalia under
extremely difficult security conditions.
</P>
<P>
WFP is seeking 14 million U.S. dollars to continue its food
distribution program throughout Somalia this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990428.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
