<P>
BEIJING, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The president of the New York
Financial Women's Association (FWA) Lenore Albom, who is here
heading a FWA delegation to China, told Xinhua in an interview
that it is encouraging to be in China, and that all the members of
the delegation have favorable views about this country.
</P>
<P>
The delegation comprises about 50 women Wall Street CEOs,
including vice presidents with the Citizens Bank and Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
The FWA was founded in 1956 by six women and has grown into an
influential organization of 1,100 members who work as bankers,
securities analysts, investors and so on.
</P>
<P>
"We are here to find investment opportunities," said Albom, who
herself is vice-president with Chase Securities, explaining that
China is in the midst of a critical transition, moving from a
central government-controlled economy to a more decentralized, and
varied one. "It is experiencing an industrial revolution and an
information revolution simultaneously, offering enormous
opportunities to the world," she added.
</P>
<P>
Each year the FWA targets an international destination and that
China has been chosen for the third time within two decades is
rare in the history of the FWA and it is an indication of the
importance China has.
</P>
<P>
After visiting Hong Kong, Shanghai and Beijing, the delegation
believes it has a fair understanding of what is going on in China.
"Everyone is excited, and agrees unanimously that the prospects
for the country are terrific," said Albom, who seemed to be
particularly impressed by the sharing of advanced U.S. technology
in some Sino-U.S. joint ventures, using the General Motors (
Shanghai) project as an example.
</P>
</TEXT>
