<HEADLINE> Anti-Poaching Police Stranded in Reserve </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Two teams of Chinese police trying
to catch poachers have been stranded in the wild Hoh Xil Nature
Reserve for three days because their cars have broken down.
</P>
<P>
The fourteen police officers from Qinghai Province are
participating in a large anti-poaching action, which was organized
by the State Forestry Administration and sponsored by Qinghai
Province and Xinjiang Uygur and Tibet autonomous regions.
</P>
<P>
Reports indicate that they now have no food or fresh water left
and are awaiting rescue teams to arrive with supplies. They are at
least 700 kilometers far away from the nearest Golmud City.
</P>
<P>
Some are apparently ill but further reports say that rescue
teams are fast approaching them.
</P>
<P>
The reserve is located on the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau, and is
home to more than 20 rare animal species like the Yak and Tibetan
antelope, which are under state protection.  
</P>
