<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Successful in Increasing Onshore Oil Recovery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 28 (Xinhua) -- After 30 odd years of scientific
research and practice, China has scored remarkable progress in
increasing crude oil recovery by developing oil polymer driven
technology, and plans to introduce it to all onshore oilfields
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
According to Han Dakuang, a senior specialist at the China
National Petroleum Corp (CNPC), most of the country's oilfields
belong to the complex continental deposits as far as reserve
layers are concerned, with thick crude and oil wells containing
more water.
</P>
<P>
He said that the polymer driven technology is the most useful
way to solve the above mentioned problems. "It has become a
pressing task to develop oil recovery technology, for two thirds
of such crude reserves remains to be extracted," he explained.
</P>
<P>
The specialist noted that as early as the 1960s, China started
interior experiments with the polymer driven technology and
achieved positive results in Xinjiang and Daqing, the country's
largest oilfield.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1980s, China has carried out six pilot experiments in
the oilfields of Daqing, Dagang and Henan, resulting in the
decline of the water content and higher crude output in these
oilfields.
</P>
<P>
Starting in the 1990s, the country expanded the experiments
into industrial production, with more satisfactory results.
</P>
<P>
The specialist said that the polymer driven technology is very
promising and more mature in terms of technological application,
which produced higher economic returns after being applied to the
country's various major oilfields.
</P>
<P>
Experiments show that injection of one ton of polymer into the
oil wells will turn out an additional 167 tons of crude.
</P>
<P>
To provide more polymer for the oilfields, the country has set
up the world's largest polymer making plant with an annual
production capacity of more than 50,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
The specialist expects the country to pump out an additional 10
million tons of crude annually by the year 2000 by spreading the
use of the new technology in the onshore oilfields nationwide.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
