<HEADLINE> Chinese Bar Association Urged to Heed Self-discipline, Defend Rights of Lawyers (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Justice Minister Gao Changli
urged the All-China Lawyers Association (ACLA) here today to play
its due role of self-discipline and defend the legitimate rights
and interests of its over 100,000 members.
</P>
<P>
"The rapidly growing contingent of lawyers is good and reliable
in the main," said Gao at the closing meeting installing the new
leadership of the ACLA, stressing that "there are still some
problems, and serious ones."
</P>
<P>
"Some lawyers are not discharging their duties by toeing the
line of the law, and lack a sense of social responsibility." he
pointed out.
</P>
<P>
"They are breaking away from the law in pursuit of economic
interest, or out of personal favoritism. Exorbitant fees were
found to have been imposed on litigants in some places," he said.
</P>
<P>
"These problems are getting worse despite repeated bans and
rectification efforts," he said, warning that they are "tarnishing
the image" of the legal profession as a whole.
</P>
<P>
"Those 'black sheep' should not be left at large, and the new
leadership must assume the responsibility of redressing such ills
and exercising self-regulation over the profession," Gao said .
</P>
<P>
He called for an immediate installation of a committee for
handling violations of ethical code of conducts in line with the
lawyers law and related regulations of the Justice Ministry.  (
