<DOCNO> XIE19990428.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Article Reveals Cruelty of Feudal Serfdom in Tibet (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The overseas edition of People's
Daily today carried an article which reveals the true condition of
Tibetan people's personal rights under feudal serfdom which ended
40 years ago, saying it was absolutely necessary to abolish the
backward and reactionary system.
</P>
<P>
An attached editor's note commented that "the article proved
the necessity to carry out the democratic reforms in Tibet in 1959
and to thoroughly abolish feudal serfdom", and refuted the Dalai
Lama's claims to be concerned about the condition of human rights
in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
In the article, the author Gyadun pointed out that personal
rights and freedom should be a key part of human rights, which,
however, were hardly enjoyed by serfs who accounted for 95 percent
of the Tibetan population in the old period.
</P>
<P>
Before the democratic reforms in 1959, Tibet was under the rule
of the Dalai Lama-led despotic theocratic authority, which was
composed of administrative officials, the nobility, and high-
ranking lamas representing only the rights and interests of serf
owners. Serfs were forced to be in bondage to the three categories
of feudal lords and were deprived of personal freedom throughout
their lives.
</P>
<P>
Under the extremely backward and reactionary system, the serfs'
fate was dominated by the owners so much that they could be beaten,
transported, presented as gifts or sold as the owners liked, the
article said.
</P>
<P>
It quoted a Tibetan archive as proving that even the marriage
of serfs could be decided by their lords. The document revealed
that an adopted daughter of a serf in the Nequng Temple, named
Lhaba, was transferred to a migrant to marry him after the
temple's senior lama paid the serf an amount of money.
</P>
<P>
In the old Tibet, the relationship between serfs and their
owners was called "mi-rtsa", or "human root", which meant that
every serf had his or her own root and had to be ruled by the lord.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990428.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Article Reveals Cruelty of Feudal Serfdom in Tibet (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In attempt to prevent serfs from escaping, the then Tibetan
administration published strict laws. For instance, an order
issued by the 13th Dalai Lama to all local governments and temples
prohibited officials and monks from sheltering runaway serfs. The
Tibetan government of the Qing Dynasty (1644-1911) set up an
official position, called "so-nam-las-khungs", to take
responsibility for recapturing escaped serfs.
</P>
<P>
A poll tax in the old Tibet, known as "mi-bogs", was another
form of serf ownership to bind them to their masters. The system
forced traveling serfs including craftsmen, peddlers and even
beggars to pay an annual poll tax to their original lords no
matter how far they traveled.
</P>
<P>
Codes in the old Tibet divided people into three classes and
nine ranks, under which values of life varied from different ranks.
Tibetan kings, living Buddhas and the nobility on the top of the
class system were described as "priceless", however people at the
bottom, including blacksmiths, butchers, hunters and women, were
merely worth a "straw rope".
</P>
<P>
With the help of the law, the serf-owners applied extremely
cruel penalties to those who defied superiors, such as the gouging
out of eyes, cutting off of feet, their tongues, or hands,
throwing people off cliffs or into water or simply executing them,
in order to maintain their rule, the article said.
</P>
<P>
Many Tibetan archives contain examples of different kinds of
instruments of torture used during the rule of Dalai Lama, as well
as photos taken in the 1950s, which depicted serfs whose eyes
were gouged out and hands or feet were cut off.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990428.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Article Reveals Cruelty of Feudal Serfdom in Tibet (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Serfs in old Tibet were divided into three classes and received
different kinds of enslavement accordingly.
</P>
<P>
People belonging to the first two classes were called khral-pa
and dud-chung. They each made up 45 percent of the total
population in old Tibet. The third class of serf, nang-gzan, which
accounted for five percent of the total population, had the lowest
social status of all three.
</P>
<P>
Feudal lords gave khral-pa, or people who rented farmland to
till, plots of land and houses which they could use for
generations. But khral-pa were not allowed to leave their land for
a long period of time or give it up. They also had to do tasks
both on the farmland and manors of their landlords and had to pay
various types of tax.
</P>
<P>
When stricken by natural disasters or accidents, some khral-pa
borrowed usurious loans from the owners to make ends meet and were
thus further burdened by heavy debts.
</P>
<P>
Numbers of khral-pa did flee their rented land and houses but
would be beaten up by their lords and downgraded to mere slaves if
they were caught.
</P>
<P>
Dud-chung, which means small households, were humbler than
khral-pa, and were not qualified to rent land. They could only
till a small plot of land to make a living and throughout their
lives had to do all kinds of labor for their feudal lords. They
lived in small and rundown houses and only received a small amount
of food as payment from their landlords. They were not allowed to
leave the manors of their landlords.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990428.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Article Reveals Cruelty of Feudal Serfdom in Tibet (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Nang-gzan, or domestic slaves, had the lowest social status in
old Tibet and endured the poorest living conditions. They were
used as "tools" by feudal lords and were deprived of any human
rights. They did not own any farming tools, domestic animals or
land. They were not even allowed to marry or have families.
</P>
<P>
Feudal lords only provided nang-gzan with a minimum of living
necessities, and forced them to do all kinds of household work and
many hard outdoor tasks. They were often maltreated by their lords
and some were beaten to death.
</P>
<P>
Before the democratic reform in Tibet, feudal lords applied a
set of strict written or unwritten laws and regulations which were
intended to deprive serfs of their human rights.
</P>
<P>
First of all, when a child was born to a serf's family, he or
she would be registered with the recorder of population, which was
part of their feudal lords domain, and lost their freedom once and
for all. Serf owners collected tax both in kind and in labor from
serfs according to this population record.
</P>
<P>
Serfs, who were regarded as the private property of their
owners, had to work for feudal lords from the age of 15 to 60
years old, and could only shake off all the labor and tax burden
after a registered death.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, serfs who belonged to the same owner and wanted to
marry each other, had to ask for consent from their owners, and
marriages between serfs who belonged to different owners were
strictly controlled. Serfs had to give a certain amount of money
to redeem themselves from their original owners if they were
married to serfs owned by other feudal lords.
</P>
<P>
Thirdly, feudal lords could deprive serfs of their personal
freedom at any time if they wanted to enlarge the production scale
of their farmland and manors, or wanted more serfs to do household
work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990428.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Article Reveals Cruelty of Feudal Serfdom in Tibet (5) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The above facts truly demonstrate that the feudal serfdom
system had seriously hindered the development of the productive
forces in Tibet, and had to be abolished.
</P>
<P>
Serf owners were only concerned with how they could exploit the
maximum amount of work and effort from serfs and slaves, but paid
no attention to their living and working conditions.
</P>
<P>
They had no idea how to improve the production tools and skills
of laborers and also did not know how to enhance productive forces
and invest properly to enlarge the production scale.
</P>
<P>
To give vent to their anger and complaints about poor living
conditions, serfs often went on a go slow in their work, made
petitions, destroyed production tools, refused to hand in tax or
paid back debts or just simply fled from their land and houses.
</P>
<P>
This resulted in large areas of farmland going to waste in
terms of cultivation, and in turn people's living standards
declined. The decreasing number of laborers in feudal manors also
led to the reduced income of feudal lords and caused economic
crisis.
</P>
<P>
In short, to abolish the feudal serfdom system in Tibet,
implement democratic reform, and get rid off the feudal hierarchy
was the only way to safeguard the human rights of Tibetan people
and provide them with equal opportunities to exercise their
political, economic and cultural rights and enjoy a happy life.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990428.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
