<DOCNO> XIE19990428.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dengue Fever Cases Rise Nearly 20 Folds in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The number of dengue fever
cases in Malaysia has increased by almost 20 folds since 1986,
Malaysian Health Minister Chua Jui Meng said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
There were only 1,408 cases with eight deaths in 1986, but the
number spiraled to 27,373 with 58 deaths in 1998, Chua told a news
conference here.
</P>
<P>
From January to April 10 this year, dengue fever cases
increased by 6 percent to 4,373 with 11 deaths compared with 4,126
cases in the corresponding period of last year, he said.
</P>
<P>
He warned of the possibility of a large-scale serious outbreak
in six hot-spot states -- Selangor, Kuala Lumpur, Perak, Pahang,
Kedah and Pulau Pinang -- if no immediate actions were taken to
clear the breeding grounds of the Aedes mosquito, the dengue
carrier.
</P>
<P>
Chua urged all government and private agencies and
non-governmental organizations to immediately conduct cleanliness
campaigns, saying the only way to arrest the dengue menace is to
get the fullest cooperation of all the people.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia launched a nationwide anti-mosquito and cleanliness
campaign on April 20 following the outbreak of the Japanese
Encephalitis (JE) and Nipah viral, which have already claimed more
than 100 lives.
</P>
<P>
Chua said that since the JE and Nipah viral outbreak had
abated, his ministry was now giving more attention to the dengue
fever menace.
</P>
<P>
Chua said most of the dengue fever cases occurred in urban
areas due to the increasing population and the rising number of
breeding places of the Aedes mosquito.
</P>
<P>
The 20-fold increase in the number of cases appeared to show
that Malaysians did not care about their surroundings anymore, he
said.
</P>
<P>
He appealed to all Malaysians to participate in the on-going
anti-mosquito campaign. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
