<HEADLINE> Definition of "Model Worker" Alters in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, April 28 (Xinhua) -- A model worker in China gives
people an impression of someone who works very hard and even gets
ill constantly because of fatigue.
</P>
<P>
But model workers who are praised today in Shenyang, capital
city of northeast China's Liaoning Province, give people another
feeling -- for they are masters of new technology and knowledge.
</P>
<P>
A new rice variety developed by Fan Xiangjiu, a farmer at a
small town called Dingtao in Tieling City, brought more than 1.4
million yuan (168,670 US dollars) in economic profits for local
people. Fan only received a junior high school education and
became a self taught agro-technician.
</P>
<P>
Stepping down form the awards rostrum, Fan said," Technology is
badly needed in the countryside and I will use my know-how to
serve the farmers".
</P>
<P>
More than 1,000 model workers were selected in Liaoning this
year and included were an increasing number of people who have
become rich by relying on science and technology.
</P>
<P>
Ten percent of the model workers are enterprise managers; the
winners covered owners of private enterprises for the first time,
making up three percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
A list of 1,000 "national model workers" came out a few days
ago, including 174 researchers and technicians. A survey shows
that 48.6 percent of them graduated from colleges for professional
training and 27.3 of them have a senior title equaling to
professor.
</P>
<P>
"Model workers in the existing market economy should not only
have a good public image in society, but help to bring huge
economic profits," said Niu Gang, president of the Dashang Group,
the largest commercial group in the northeastern part of the
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
