<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian Soccer Club Has No Money For Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Zambian Football Association of
Zambia (FAZ) has said it has no money to hold elections to chose
its new leadership as being demand by the government.
</P>
<P>
Times of Zambia Wednesday quoted a FAZ source as saying that it
does not have the means to comply with the government directive to
put in office a new executive by May 7 to replace the out-of-favor
Teddy Mulonga administration.
</P>
<P>
Sports Council of Zambia (SCZ) General Secretary Mattew
Mulwanda was quoted as saying that "as far as the council is
concerned, the deadline of May 7 is still in force. We'll talk
about it when it lapses."
</P>
<P>
But another council member said the FAZ is merely time buying,
especially knowing FIFA is behind it.
</P>
<P>
"It would be just another tactic to buy time," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mulonga won a confidence vote 34-30 at the council meeting of
the FAZ held last February but the government ignored the result
and ordered new elections within 45 days.
</P>
<P>
Mulonga's executive has been under government squeeze since
April last year when his executive was dissolved by SCZ over
allegations that it had misapplied 577 million kwacha (about 230,
000 U.S. dollars) of a government grant given to it for last
year's Africa Cup of Nations finals in Burkina Faso.
</P>
<P>
The FAZ has been going though financial difficulties since the
government withdrew support to show its displeasure with the
association's national executive led by Teddy Mulonga.
</P>
<P>
Following Zambia's poor performance at the Africa Cup finals in
Burkina Faso in February of 1998, the FAZ executive was removed
two months later on the charge of misapplication of the money the
government released for the campaign.
</P>
<P>
World soccer governing body FIFA, reacting to what it saw as
government interference in the running of soccer, was on the verge
of banning Zambia from international football activities when the
government reluctantly restored in office the FAZ executive led by
Mulonga.
</P>
<P>
The government allowed in September in 1998 Mulonga and his
team back in office but it imposed a financial squeeze on the
association in a bid to force the current executive out.
</P>
<P>
The estrangement of the FAZ executive has cast a shadow on the
future of Zambian football given the fact the association is
dependent on the government financial support to fulfill its
various international engagements.
</P>
<P>
Last month government spokesman Newstead Zambia said that the
government is waiting for a new FAZ executive to be elected before
it could once again begin to provide the financial, moral and
logistical support it withdrew from the FAZ last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
