<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NPC Session Discusses Donation Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The draft law on public welfare
donations is of great significance to the nation and should be
approved as soon as possible, according to participants in the
ongoing ninth session of China's top legislature.
</P>
<P>
The law will enhance protection of the legal interests of both
donors and beneficiaries, and further promote the social economic
development of the country, it was declared.
</P>
<P>
Gan Ziyu, a member of the Standing Committee of the Chinese
National People's Congress (NPC), said that as donations to
charities are becoming more popular than ever, more problems have
also popped up.
</P>
<P>
"It is imperative to have legislation that will regulate the
activities," he said.
</P>
<P>
The draft law decrees that only public welfare organizations,
non-profit making institutions and government departments at
county level or above are entitled to accept such donations.
</P>
<P>
In the discussions, some participants said the scope should be
enlarged, especially when it comes to numerous, small donations,
and that the law should pay more attention to the will of donors.
</P>
<P>
They expressed the hope that government departments, whenever
possible, should not receive donations so as to avoid the
conflicts of interests.
</P>
<P>
During the discussions, there was much disagreement over
whether the draft legislation includes the practice of soliciting
donations.
</P>
<P>
Li Yining, a member of the NPC Standing Committee and noted
economist, said the draft law on donations should exclude
soliciting as to combine the two issues in one legislation would
create confusion.
</P>
<P>
"The draft should also make it more specific on the
preferential measures to be used to attract more donations," said
Gu Songfen, another member of the committee.
</P>
<P>
Some suggested that the draft provide confidentiality to those
donors who prefer not to have their contributions made public.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
