<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 28 (Xinhua) -- A court hearing started today
into the major fire that destroyed Beijing's Yuquanying Furniture
Center, the largest furniture market in the Chinese capital, last
year.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 observers watched as the two men accused of
responsibility for the fire, 37-year-old Zhang Jianguo and 54-
year-old Wang Jinlai, stood in the main hall of the People's Court
of Dongcheng District as official prosecutors read out details of
the case.
</P>
<P>
On the evening of May 5 last year, the Yuquanying Furniture
Center, covering 18,000 sq m and located in Fengtai District, some
ten km from Tiananmen Square, was burned to the ground.
</P>
<P>
The economic loss caused by the blaze is estimated at 20.87
million yuan. The first batch of compensation of five million yuan
(about 620,000 US dollars) has already been paid by Huatai
Insurance Ltd, according to earlier reports.
</P>
<P>
According to experts the fire was caused due to the overheating
of an electric bell's coil.
</P>
<P>
The final verdict will be handed down after the court
investigations are completed in several days time, according to
information from the Dongcheng People's Court. 
