<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The Australian stock market
retreated from a record high into negative territory Wednesday
after the release of inflation figures appeared to dash hopes of
an interest rate cut in the short term.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark All Ordinaries Index fell 22.5 points to 3,122.7
at the close, down from its record intra-day peak of 3,156.9
points.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's retreat followed four consecutive record breaking
closes for the All Ordinaries.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Bureau of Statistics Wednesday reported that the
consumer price index (CPI) fell 0.1 percent in the first quarter
of this year, for an annual inflation rate of 1.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the All Industrials Index shed 42.3 points to
5,541.3 and the All Resources Index retreated 5.6 points to
1,172.6.
</P>
<P>
The banking index slumped 66.9 points to 7,493, with all major
bank stocks down.
</P>
<P>
ANZ bank tumbled 20.5 cents to 12.243 Australian dollars,
National Australia Bank offloaded 19.4 cents to 29.706 Australian
dollars, Commonwealth Bank of Australia dipped 15 cents to 27.95
Australian dollars and Westpac bank slid 12 cents to 11.88
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Among resource stocks, diversified miner BHP lost 21 cents to
16.16 Australian dollars and global miner Rio Tinto fell 28.5
cents to 25.165 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index lost 0.2 of a point to close at 984.1.
</P>
<P>
The spot price of gold bullion in Sydney closed Wednesday
afternoon at 282.70 U.S. dollars an ounce, compared with a close
of 281.2 U.S. dollars Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 529.24 million stocks traded for 907.25
million U.S. dollars. Falling stocks outnumbered rising ones 787
to 620 and 518 stocks remained steady. 
