<HEADLINE> China Eastern Airlines Reports Loss in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The China Eastern Airlines
Corporation Ltd. (CEA), one of China's top three airways, reported
a loss of 632.4 million yuan in 1998 in its annual report
published in today's Shanghai Securities News.
</P>
<P>
The report showed that the CEA's business proceeds stood at 8.6
billion yuan in 1998, falling from the previous year's 9.4 billion
yuan. However, the company suffered a severe loss last year
against a reported profit of 332 million yuan in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Earnings per share also sank from 0.068 yuan in 1997 to minus 0.
13 yuan in 1998.
</P>
<P>
An analysis in the report attributed the loss to a sluggish
demand in the aviation market both at home and in Asia, as well as
the cut-throat price war in the industry.
</P>
<P>
To tackle the difficulties, the CEA will adopt new measures
this year including modernizing its fleet by selling old planes
and buying new jets and expanding code sharing business with
international airways, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1998, the CEA had an asset value of 27 billion
yuan, with 71 planes flying on 129 air routes, including 21
international lines.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
