<HEADLINE> Tanzania Plans Fresh Crackdown on Int'l Crimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania will launch a
fresh crackdown on international crimes together with other
African countries, a senior police officer has said.
</P>
<P>
The police plan to identify possible targets before the action
is taken, Adadi Rajabu, director of Criminal Investigations, was
quoted as saying by Wednesday's "The Guardian" newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The operation will be carried out with the assistance of other
Southern African Development Community (SADC) countries, as well
as Kenya and Uganda, Rajabu said, adding that tactics will be
similar to those of last year's crackdown on cross-border crimes.
</P>
<P>
Last August, the nationwide swoop recovered more than 160
automobiles stolen from Tanzania, South Africa, Malawi and
Swaziland.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the police seized 27 guns and eight bullets,
cracked 13 drug cases and arrested a number of suspects.
</P>
<P>
Rajabu said Tuesday that another meeting involving the
International Police (Interpol) from the 14 SADC countries is
likely to be held in north
Tanzania's Arusha town. 
</P>
</TEXT>
