<DOCNO> XIE19990428.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Leonean President Challenges Rebels to Polls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Sierra Leonean President Ahmed
Tejan Kabbah has urged the rebel Revolutionary United Front (RUF)
to "renounce violence and terror", and challenged them to meet at
the polling booth in less than 15 months' time.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the nation in a broadcast to mark 38th anniversary
of independence on Tuesday, the president said that coup and
counter-coup which have plagued the country since independence
"have not solved any of our economic, social and political
problems", The Guardian newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Since 1961, Sierra Leone has seen four major military coup
d'etats, two counter-coup d'etats, at least five attempted ones
and four palace coup d' etats in addition to eight years of bloody
rebellion.
</P>
<P>
Kabbah noted that coup and counter-coup "have increased the
number and complexity of our problems", resulting in "wanton
killings of kith and kin".
</P>
<P>
He announced that an independent human rights commission would
be set up shortly "to strengthen existing mechanisms for the
protection of the basic rights of all Sierra Leoneans".
</P>
<P>
Kabbah made no direct reference to a statement by rebel leader
Foday Sankoh in Togo on Monday that he was prepared to declare a
ceasefire "which could be immediate, temporary or definitive."
</P>
<P>
In Lome, capital of Togo, 19 representatives of the RUF who
arrived last weekend are holding informal discussions with Sankoh
who was released temporarily from prison in Freetown for the
consultations with his followers.
</P>
<P>
The consultations are seen as a precursor to actual peace talks
between the rebels and the Kabbah government.
</P>
<P>
Togolese President Gnassingbe Eyadema, current chairman of the
Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS), is closely
following the consultations along with ECOWAS Executive Secretary
Lansana Kouyate and envoys from the Organization of African Unity
(OAU).
</P>
<P>
On the ground, the two sides of the Sierra Leone conflict are
fiercely defending their positions. The West African
peace-keeping force of ECOMOG holds capital Freetown and its
vicinity while the rebels control several strategic points
including the country's second largest city of Makeni. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
