<HEADLINE> Informal Traders to Be Organized in Mozambique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Ramos Marrengula, Chairman of the
newly formed Association of the Informal Traders in Maputo,
capital of Mozambique, has vowed to unite all the small traders
for organized business.
</P>
<P>
Marrengula, who is the initiator for one of the biggest market
for informal traders, said that his organization will try to bring
all those involved in informal business into the new organization,
saying that proper measures will be taken by the police for those
who refuse to enter the organization in the southern African
country.
</P>
<P>
The organization will consult with the police authorities on
the problems of stolen goods in some markets, Marrengula said.
</P>
<P>
There are about 17,000 people involved in informal business in
Maputo, a city with one million population. The informal traders
are those who do their business in the city without registration
or any other legal process, many believe that these traders are
offering market for stolen goods.  
</P>
</TEXT>
