<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Horti-Expo Weathers Tests by Abnormal Weather Conditions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Flowers and plants growing in the
gardens of the China '99 Kunming International Horticultural
Exposition are facing another severe challenge as the temperature
fell to a new low of 11.4 Celsius degrees this morning.
</P>
<P>
Information from the local weather station shows that the cold
weather is the result of the invasion by a cold current from
northern China.
</P>
<P>
Known as a "city of eternal spring", Kunming has experienced
abnormal weather conditions ever since the beginning of this year,
including heavy snow in the spring, followed by a long hot and dry
spell and the allegedly early arrival of the rainy season.
</P>
<P>
However, the rare flowers and plants at the '99 horticultural
exposition have successfully tided over the abnormal weather
conditions thanks to the meticulous care by gardeners.
</P>
<P>
The horticultural exposition, scheduled to open on May 1, is
hailed to have gathered an unprecedentedly great number of plants.
There are more than 500,000 square meters of turf, about 430,000
trees and shrubs of more than 2,000 species, and more than one
million pots of flowers.
</P>
<P>
An unusually heavy snow hit the city in mid-January, covering
up the whole Expo site for days. About one-third of the plastics-
covered greenhouses and sheds collapsed, with some of the tree
branches ruptured and many tropical and sub-tropical flowers and
plants endangered.
</P>
<P>
The whole city moved quickly to clear the snow and rescue the
rare species.
</P>
<P>
From early February to some days ago, the city fell into the
grip of a long hot and dry spell, with the highest temperature
reaching 30 Celsius degrees, close to the record 31.7 Celsius
degrees. All the irrigation facilities were called up, including
fire engines, to carry water from a nearby reservoir to the Expo
site.
</P>
<P>
The gardeners working there had to water the plants and flowers
at least twice a day, and even ten times for some species.
</P>
<P>
A local meteorological official dismissed the worry about a
possible early arrival of the rainy season. "The rain last night
is favorable to the flowers and plants at the Expo site, since
most of the plants are tropical, sub-tropical and temperate, quite
used to the humid environment," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
