<DOCNO> XIE19990428.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Bleeds as Brain Drain Continues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The South African government
lost 8.4 billion rand (1.4 billion U.S. dollars) of potential
income tax as a result of brain drain between 1994 and 1997,
Business Day newspaper Wednesday quoted a study as showing.
</P>
<P>
The emigration of graduates and professionals in the four years
cost the South African economy 285 billion rand (47.5 billion
dollars) in potential contributions to overall GDP.
</P>
<P>
The study, compiled by Reinhold Joubert, associate professor of
 economics at the University of South Africa, concludes that the
costs of emigration may not appear drastic in a single year, but
it will in the long run.
</P>
<P>
"Emigration is like syrup running from a spoon. If it starts to
run, it is difficult to stop."
</P>
<P>
South Africa was regarded as an immigration country until
1994, but has become an emigration country. Factors in the change
include crime, expectations of economic growth and potential
earnings and the promulgation of the Employment Equity Act.
</P>
<P>
The researchers say emigration is a rational response to the
act, which is aimed at making the work place representative of the
racial breakdown of the population as quickly as possible.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990428.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyans Urged to Guard Against Undue Foreign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi
has called for caution in the privatization process in Kenya,
saying it should be selective to safeguard local enterprises from
undue foreign influence.
</P>
<P>
Moi told those involved in privatization process to ensure that
the affected enterprises were not conduits for inferior foreign
goods into the country, he was quoted as saying by Wednesday's
Kenya Times newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Noting the country was poised for newly industrialized status
by 2020, Moi told entrepreneurs to ensure that local industries
did not close because of the dumping of cheap imports into local
markets.
</P>
<P>
Moi made these remarks Tuesday at the Abothuguci Secondary
School in Meru Central District in Eastern Province.
</P>
<P>
The president also called for prudent use of all money
acquired from the World Bank and the International Monetary Fund,
noting that all these money were loans that shall be repaid.
</P>
<P>
Moi pointed out that the globalization of the world economy
required that individual countries manage their affairs more
prudently.
</P>
<P>
In this connection, the president called for proper management
of the coffee and tea industries, saying that agriculture is the
backbone of the country's economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
