<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N.Zealand Welcomes Chile's Action in Protecting IPR </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, April 28 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand has expressed its
appreciation for Chile's action of destroying all New
Zealand-developed apple trees illegally grown in that country,
local media reports said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The reports quoted Pat Murray, strategic marketing general
manager of Enza, the exporting trading arm of New Zealand's Apple
and Pear Marketing Board, as saying that Enza has greatly
appreciated Chile's prompt and positive affirmation of
international legislation to protect intellectual property rights
(IPR).
</P>
<P>
Enza's concern became public in January when it said it had
discovered 65,000 Sciros trees growing in Chile. The Sciros trees
produce patented Pacific Rose apples developed by the Horticulture
and Food Research Institute of New Zealand. Under the
international Plant Variety Rights Agreement, which Chile signed
last year, it is illegal for any country to grow plant varieties
patented by other growers.
</P>
<P>
Destroying all New Zealand-developed apple trees by Chile has
created a more favorable atmosphere for New Zealand Prime Minister
Jenny Shipley to visit the country next month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
