<DOCNO> XIE19990428.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Home Sales Hit Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, April 27 (Xinhua) -- U.S. March existing home
sales rose 0.6 percent to a record 5.05 million units from 5.02
million units in February, according to the National Association
of Realtors (NAR) Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
March resales were up 3.7 percent from 4.87 million units a
year ago in March 1998, the NAR added.
</P>
<P>
"A combination of factors -- excellent housing affordability
conditions and a strong desire by consumers to buy -- are keeping
the market incredibly strong," NAR president Sharon Millett said.
"The months ahead look very promising."
</P>
<P>
By region, March resales were strongest in the West, where they
rose 2.8 percent, and weakest in the Northeast, which had a 2.7
percent drop last month. Sales rose 0.8 percent in the Midwest but
were unchanged in the South.
</P>
<P>
The NAR said the median price for an existing home was 132,700
U.S. dollars in March, up from 129,500 dollars in February and
also up from 127,100 dollars a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Analysts cited a robust labor market, affordable interest rates
and strong consumer demand as reasons behind the record increase.
</P>
<P>
"We've got an economy, I think, that is going to be unmatched
historically, possible going clearly into the year 2000," NAR vice
president Fred Flick told a news conference. "We are forecasting 3.
5 percent real growth in 1999."
</P>
<P>
The country's unemployment rate and 30-year mortgage rates
remained low during the first three months of 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
