<DOCNO> XIE19990428.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-US Haven for Plants Planned in Southwestern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, April 28 (Xinhua) -- China and the United States are
planning to invest five million US dollars to build a "botanical
haven" in southwestern China's Yunnan province in order to protect
the biological and cultural diversity there and help local people
eliminate poverty.
</P>
<P>
About the size of Ireland, the area will be a demonstrative
area for sustainable development. The Nature Conservancy of the
United States will contribute two million US dollars and Yunnan
Province will contribute three million US dollars, according to
Yunnan provincial officials.
</P>
<P>
Researchers of the two sides will cooperate closely in
protecting forests and endangered species of animals and in
controlling water loss and soil erosion, according to the
agreement.
</P>
<P>
With a population of three million, the botanical haven is one
of the ten areas that are the most biodiversified in the world and
is home to such endangered animals as Yunnan golden monkey and
lesser panda.
</P>
<P>
The area is also one of the world's most important national
cultural heritage protection areas which are inhabited by more
than ten minority nationalities, each with a history of thousands
of years. The ancient city Lijiang, built by the ancestors of the
Naxi people, has been listed as one of the world's cultural
heritage. The written language used by the Naxi people is the only
pictograph still in use in the world.
</P>
<P>
Inaccessibility has held back the economic development in the
area. There are still more than 600,000 people in the areas who
have not solved the problem of inadequate food and clothing.
Poverty has resulted in over-dependency and excessive exploitation
of the natural resources, posing a mounting pressure and threat to
the ecological environment there.
</P>
<P>
"The quality of the ecological environment in the area also has
a direct bearing on the life of billions of residents in southern
and southeastern Asian countries since the upstreams of the
Yangtze River, the Mekong River and the Nujiang River all flow
past the area," said a provincial official.
</P>
<P>
Sustainable development, advocated by the United Nations as a
global program of action, requires increasing global cooperation
to better protect and manage the global ecological system.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that the project will find a way for both mountainous
areas that have not been much damaged and regions inhabited by
ethnic groups to attain economic prosperity while effectively
protecting the ecology," said Hao Jianxiu, vice minister of the
State Development Planning Commission.
</P>
<P>
A group of experts and officials from both sides have gathered
here. They are required to complete a plan for the massive project
in 18 months and work out policies and rules and regulations that
will ensure the implementation of the plan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990428.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian-Congolese Border Reopened </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Acting chief government spokesman
of Zambia,

Bennie Mwiinga, said that Zambian government is still negotiating
with DRC over the release of the five Zambians, who were detained
by the heavily- armed DRC soldiers last Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
The border post at Kasumbalesa in the north of Zambia has been
reopened, after its was closed Monday morning after five Zambian
surveyors were picked up and detained by government soldiers of
the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
The border was reopened late Monday afternoon following
intensive negotiations between government officials of the two
countries, Zambia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
But the five Zambians abducted last Saturday have not yet been
released despite assurances by the captors that they would be
freed.
</P>
<P>
The five were on government duty checking the border line west
of Kasumbalesa barrier when the armed Congolese soldiers pounced
them and dragged them into their side.
</P>
<P>
The Zambians were accused of carrying out military data for the
rebels fighting to topple DRC President Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
Later, the authorities of DRC have refused to free the five
Zambians and instead they have made fresh demands that five
unknown Congolese allegedly being held in Zambia for unknown
reasons be swapped, the news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The new demand took aback the Zambian reception team which was
at Kasumbalesa border post the whole day to receive the expected
freed Zambians.
</P>
<P>
Chijingu expressed profound disappointment at the turn of
events considering the promises the Congolese made on Monday to
free the Zambians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
