<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandan Police Officer Accused of Taking Bribe in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- A Ugandan police officer in
charge of criminal investigations was charged with accepting a
bribe of 100 million shillings (100,000 U.S. dollar) to block
probe into a murder case.
</P>
<P>
Chris Bakiza, director of the Criminal Investigations
Department (CID), is said to have accepted the bribe from city
tycoon Karim Hirji to stop investigations into the 1997 murder of
motor rally driver Gerald Kiddu, the New Vision newspaper reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The allegations are contained in the terms of reference of the
newly- formed Judicial Commission of Inquiry into corruption in
the police force.
</P>
<P>
Bakiza is now on a six-month forced leave and is barred from
leaving the country without permission of the internal affairs
minister.
</P>
<P>
Kiddu, a business associate of Karim, was killed in 1997 by
unknown assailants at a friend's house in Bunga near Kampala. At
the time of his death he had been a rally driver while also being
employed by Dembe Enterprises, a company owned by Karim.
</P>
<P>
Bakiza is also accused of defying orders from the former
Inspector General of Police Cossy Odomel. He is said to have
defied orders to take actions on one Kalyango who had been
arrested on charges of highway robbery.
</P>
<P>
Bakiza's case, together with Cossy Odomel who was recently
removed from office on charges of abuse of office and corruption,
contributed to the transference of former Internal Affairs
Minister Tom Butime to another ministerial post in the latest
cabinet reshuffle. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
