<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PNG Stock Exchange Launched </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The Port Moresby Stock Exchange
in Papua New Guinea (PNG) was officially launched Wednesday and
began a trial period of trading.
</P>
<P>
PNG Commerce and Industry Minister Ian Ling-Stuckey said the
launch of the stock exchange was crucial to the PNG government's
attempts to successfully conclude the PNG's first sovereign bond
issue, the Australian Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the launch in Port Moresby, capital of the South
Pacific nation, PNG Prime Minister Bill Skate said the stock
exchange would be of tremendous benefit to the people of PNG.
</P>
<P>
"When it is open for business, the Port Moresby stock exchange
will open doors to increased foreign investments ... and it will
create job opportunities for our people," Skate said.
</P>
<P>
A PNG stock exchange has been discussed since the mid-1970s
but enabling legislation, the Securities Act, was only passed in
March 1997.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister promised that his government would not
interfere in the operations of the stock exchange.
</P>
<P>
"My government has no intention of interfering with statutory
bodies," Skate said in his keynote address at the launch.
</P>
<P>
"We only interfere when we know there is no productivity. We
only interfere when we know they're not producing results."
</P>
<P>
Last year the government attempted to appoint its own chairman
of the stock exchange, AAP said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
