<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Expert Finds Way to Tackle CIH Virus Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 28 (Xinhua) - A leading Chinese computer expert
has worked out an effective way to repair the hard drives of
computers that are damaged by the CIH Chernobyl virus.
</P>
<P>
Liu Xu, chief engineer of Beijing-based Rising Company, China's
leading anti-virus company, told Xinhua today that his team has
succeeded in designing a program that is capable of restoring most
of the data on CIH-rocked disks.
</P>
<P>
Liu's team worked overnight to find the solution after the
Rising Company received reports that more than 100,000 computers
nationwide were affected on April 26.
</P>
<P>
"The program has been added to the upgraded version of the anti-
CIH software developed by the company and is now available for
users across the country," Liu said.
</P>
<P>
CIH is a widely distributed virus with the potential to render
PCs useless. Its payload results in a significant loss of data
from the hard drive, as well as the possible inability to start up
or reboot the computer.
</P>
<P>
The virus had been timed to strike on April 26, June 26 or each
26th to mark the anniversary of the Chernobyl nuclear disaster in
the former Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
The total economic losses from the virus may amount to millions
of yuan, according to Liu.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
