<HEADLINE> S. African Electricity Supplier Makes Profit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Eskom, South African
Electricity supplier, has made a gross profit of more than 150
million rand (25 million U.S. dollars) by selling electricity in
Africa last year, Sowetan newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Eskom's electrification drive is progressing well despite the
high cost related to its domestic rural electrifying program,
Peter Adams, an official of the company said.
</P>
<P>
In 1991, 32 percent of houses in South Africa had electricity
and to date more than 60 percent, including rural houses are
electrified.
</P>
<P>
"We hope to achieve the 70 percentage mark by next year," Adams
was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Adams said that his company would continue to show commitment
to its rural electrification program although this costs the
company one million rand (about 167,000 U.S. dollars) a kilometer
to provide transmission lines to remote rural homes.
</P>
<P>
South Africa, the largest producer and consumer of electricity
in the sub-equatorial region, accounts for 85 percent of
electricity consumption in the Southern African Development
Community.
</P>
<P>
Botswana, bordering with South Africa, has proven to be a good
market for South African power, Eskom said.
</P>
<P>
According to Eskom, Botswana is trying to be self-sufficient in
power supply but it takes time to build its own big power
stations.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
