<DOCNO> XIE19990428.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S'pore Moves for Stricter Foreign Workers Management </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, April 28 (Xinhua)-- Singapore launched a new work
permit identification system Wednesday as part of its efforts to
evolve a tougher and more comprehensive foreign manpower
management system.
</P>
<P>
Officiating the new work permit services center, Minister of
State for Manpower Othman Haron Eusofe said every foreign worker
in Singapore will have to replace his or her current Work Permit
Card from May 3, 1999, with the new work permit identification
card.
</P>
<P>
The new card combines the current Work Permit Card, the
Immigration Disembarkation/Embarkation Card and the Visit Pass in
one card as well as carry his or her photograph and fingerprint
record and incorporate more effective security features.
</P>
<P>
The security features will minimize the likelihood of forgery
and the fingerprints impressions will allow the enforcement
agencies a conclusive means of identifying the card holder, Eusofe
said.
</P>
<P>
Eusofe said there are more than 450,000 foreign work permit
holders in Singapore and the presence of a large pool of foreign
workers has brought some social problems. "It has become
imperative for us to better manage these foreign workers during
their stay in Singapore."
</P>
<P>
According to Eusofe, a total of 2,952 foreigners were found
working illegally in Singapore without valid work permits in 1998,
about twice the number of such cases in 1997, and an increasing
number of illegal workers were also immigration offenders which
accounted for 44 percent of illegal workers compared with the 21
percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Eusofe said the increasing number of illegal workers and the
rising incidence of forged work permit cards have made it more
difficult for enforcement officers to identify foreign workers.
</P>
<P>
He said the new cards will be jointly issued to its holders in
phases by the Singapore Immigration and Registration and the Work
Permit Department.
</P>
<P>
Eusofe reiterated that work permit holders are required to
carry work permit cards with them and the government intends to
enforce this work permits condition strictly.
</P>
<P>
Employers who retain the original work permit identification
card will risk being debarred from employing foreign workers while
the workers may be liable to have their work permits canceled or
themselves repatriated for not carrying the work permit card, he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
