<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Turkish Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The following are the major news
items in leading Turkish newspapers on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Sabah (Morning):
</P>
<P>
-- Necmettin Cevher, strong man of the central-right True Path
Party (DYP), pressed former prime minister and DYP leader Tansu
Ciller to resign and to take the responsibility for the party's
election results.
</P>
<P>
After meeting with Ciller, Cevher said that no one can be
happy with the results. The DYP ranked the fifth by winning 12.03
percent of the votes in the parliamentary and local elections held
on April 18.
</P>
<P>
Hurriyet (Freedom):
</P>
<P>
-- On the formation of a new coalition, Turkish Prime Minister
and Democratic Left Party leader Bulent Ecevit said that "there
are some points still remaining as unknown. I am thinking of
different possibilities."
</P>
<P>
Ecevit will meet with other political party leaders in the
parliament in an effort to form the new coalition next week.
</P>
<P>
Milliyet (National):
</P>
<P>
-- Turkey's Supreme Board of Election announced the results of
the parliamentary and local elections held on April 18.
</P>
<P>
The central-left Democratic Left Party (DSP) took the lead in
the 21st parliamentary elections by winning 22.17 percent of the
counted votes of over 37 million registered voters.
</P>
<P>
The right-wing Nationalist Movement Party (MHP) stood the
second by winning 17.90 percent of the votes, the pro-Islamic
Virtue Party (FP) ranked the third with 15.39 percent, the
central-right Motherland Party (ANAP) the fourth with 13.22
percent and the central-right True Path Party (DYP) the fifth
with 12.03 percent of the votes. 
</P>
