<DOCNO> XIE19990428.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Quarter Sees Steady Growth in Commodities Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The first quarter of this year
saw a steady growth in China's commodities market, Ding Junfa,
deputy director of the State Administration of Internal Trade (
SAIT) said at a news conference here today.
</P>
<P>
The total retail sales volume of consumer goods hit 760.4
billion yuan, up 7.4 percent year on year in the first quarter.
When price fluctuation is factored in, it is 10.6 percent in real
terms.
</P>
<P>
As a result of increased fixed asset investment in
infrastructure facilities, positive change was seen in the capital
goods market, with demand continuing to pick up and sales
remaining notably brisk, he said.
</P>
<P>
The total value of sales of capital goods was 858.4 billion
yuan during the first three months, up seven percent or 10 percent
in real terms.
</P>
<P>
Commodity prices continued to fall during the same period. The
retail price index dropped by 2.9 percent and residents' consumer
price fell by 1.4 percent. The price of vegetable, aquatic
products, and meat, poultry and eggs decreased respectively by 17.
3 percent, 8.1 percent and 7.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
Pork meat dropped a remarkable 20 percent in the same period.
</P>
<P>
However, Ding also cautioned that there are still difficulties
such as sluggish domestic demand, a continuing price fall of
consumer goods and the high cost of the means of production.
</P>
<P>
He said that the SAIT is to enhance market exploration, in the
rural sector in particular, in a bid to stimulate domestic
consumption.
</P>
<P>
He predicts that the nation's commodities market is to maintain
steady growth in the first half of this year and there will not be
notable ups and downs of prices.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990428.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State Councilor Meets U.S. Blood Technology Corp. President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Chinese State Councilor Wu Yi
said here today that the idea of establishing a "blood bank" in
China is promising as China is a huge populated country in
desperate need of blood.
</P>
<P>
Wu made the remarks when meeting this afternoon with Brund
Deglaire, the international president of the U.S.-based Blood
Technology Corp., who is here to sign an agreement with Wuzhong
Instrument and Meter Corp. Ltd., based in midwest China's Ningxia
Hui Autonomous Region, on "realizing safe composition transfusion
in China".
</P>
<P>
The two companies are scheduled to reach agreement on a
cooperative project for producing blood transfusion-related
instruments using the U.S. technology. Further cooperation in
setting up a "blood bank" is expected on condition that initial,
elementary cooperation has been successful.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
