<HEADLINE> NATO Strikes on Yugoslavia Continue Into 36th Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, April 28 (Xinhua) -- NATO aircraft bombed Belgrade
early Wednesday, the 36th day of the alliance's strikes, as
Yugoslav rescue workers continued to search for survivors in the
wreckage of civilian installations in a southern Serbian town
raided by NATO.
</P>
<P>
Seven powerful explosions shook the capital after air-raid
sirens were sounded around 01:00 local time. The official Tanjug
news agency said the bombings destroyed a fuel depot 100
kilometers southwest of Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, rescue workers pulled out 10 bodies and 20 injured
persons from debris in residential quarters hit by NAT0 missiles
in downtown Surdulica, about 300 kilometers south of Belgrade. The
toll number could far exceed those figures.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, NATO missiles fell on residential districts in
Surdulica, Leskovac and Podgorica.
</P>
<P>
A NATO spokesman admitted in Brussels overnight that civilian
deaths could not be excluded in the attack, saying that "...
unfortunately we cannot completely exclude the possibility of harm
to civilians, or to civilian property during a conflict such as
this one."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Serbian Health Minister Leposava Milicevic told a
press conference here that more than 400 Serbian civilians have
been killed and over 4,000 injured since NATO launched airstrikes
on March 24. 
</P>
</TEXT>
