<HEADLINE> China Preparing for More Open Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 28 (Xinhua) -- China will take measures to
ensure the stability of its agricultural market while it is
opening further to the world market.
</P>
<P>
Huang Hai, spokesman for the State Administration of Internal
Trade, told a press conference here today, that government at all
levels will set up storage markets for major agricultural products.
</P>
<P>
China has signed an agricultural cooperation agreement with the
United States, which is seen as the first real agreement between
the two governments toward China's entry into the World Trade
Organization.
</P>
<P>
International competition is expected to intensify the existing
over supply of major agricultural products such as vegetables,
meat, poultry and eggs.
</P>
<P>
Huang said a 100,000-ton storage facility has been set up for
pork, aiming to check the slumping price of pork in the first
quarter of the year.
</P>
<P>
In addition to shouldering the pressure from suppliers, the
central government will work on smoother and quicker
transportation of excessive agricultural goods to consuming
regions.
</P>
<P>
Prices for agricultural products will gradually move toward the
international level, Huang said.
</P>
<P>
While actively preparing the agricultural market for the WTO
accession, China does not expect the entry to greatly affect the
domestic retail market, Huang said.
</P>
<P>
But this market will be "gradually" opened, he said.
</P>
<P>
Overseas-funded retailers only control 5 percent of the
nation's total retailing business volume.  
</P>
</TEXT>
