<HEADLINE> UNDP-Aided Sugar Beet Project for Northeast China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Development
Program (UNDP) and the Chinese Government have jointly launched a
sugar beet development project in northeast China, which will
benefit some 72,000 poverty-stricken local farmers.
</P>
<P>
Yannick Glemarec, UNDP deputy resident representative in China,
signed the project's contract today with Sun Yongfu, deputy
director general of the China International Center for Economic
and Technical Exchanges, the official Chinese coordinator of the
project.
</P>
<P>
The project will be carried out in four towns in Hailun and
Ning'an counties, in northeast China's Heilongjiang Province, a
leading sugar beet producing area in China, within two years,
according to Glemarec.
</P>
<P>
The project will cover a training program for technical staff
and farmers, with technical assistance provided by international
specialists, a demonstration program which will include the
setting up of township-based demonstration sites for a variety of
sugar beet culture growing tests, and the provision of advanced
breeding equipment and office equipment for the Farmer Information
Centers, and transport for the demonstration program.
</P>
<P>
The UNDP will assist the project by injecting 750,000 U.S.
dollars, with funding from the Danish International Development
Agency through the UN Office for Projects Services.
</P>
<P>
A major sugar beet producer in Europe, Denmark is recognized
for its world advanced expertise in sugar beet production and
sugar making.
</P>
<P>
"Denmark will provide technical assistance, which will include
sending technicians to the project areas in northeast China," said
Franz-Michael Mellbin, a counselor at the Royal Danish Embassy.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Government will contribute the equivalent of 112,
500 U.S. dollars as a cash contribution.
</P>
<P>
"One of the priorities of the UNDP is poverty elimination,
which is also the priority of the Chinese Government," said Song
Yongfu. "We believe the project will contribute to that target."
</P>
<P>
Over the past 20 years of China-UNDP cooperation, a total of
800 projects have been implemented in China, involving some 500
million U.S. dollars, according to Sun. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
