<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 300-year Old Incense Cedar Transplanted to '99 Expo-site </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Chinese horticulturists have
successfully transplanted a 300-year-old incense cedar to the
Tree Garden of the China '99 Kunming International Horticultural
Exposition, which is to open here on May 1.
</P>
<P>
Standing aloft by the entrance to the Tree Garden, the cedar
was moved there in April last year from a village 76 kilometers
from Kunming, capital of southwestern China's Yunnan Province.
</P>
<P>
"The old tree has completely acclimatized itself to the new
environment and began to flower and bear fruit not long ago," said
Jiang Zhixiang, a senior engineer in charge of the transplantation
project.
</P>
<P>
The tree stands 13.8 meters. The trunk measures 1.2 meters in
diameter and the huge crown measures 64 square meters. Farmers in
its native place love it and adore it as "Old Tree God".
</P>
<P>
The wood of the tree is hard and resistant to corrosion and has
a strong fragrance. It is an endangered species under state-class
protection.
</P>
<P>
"To move the cedar without harming the over-stretched entangled
roots, we used two huge cranes, one carrying the upper part and
the other carrying the bottom part," recalled Jiang.
</P>
<P>
The tree withstood the acid tests by a heavy snow last spring
and is now full of vitality, Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
One of the six outdoor specialized exhibition areas, the Tree
Garden has three sub-gardens, devoted respectively to the family
of Mongolia, plants of rare or endangered species, and cash trees.
A total of 700 rare or endangered plants in 51 species grow in the
garden, which receive first- and second-class state protection.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
