<HEADLINE> UAE Company to Buy Stake in S. Korean Oil Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The Abu Dhabi-based
International Petroleum Investment Co. (IPIC) will take a 50
percent stake in Hyundai Oil Refinery Co. of South Korea.
</P>
<P>
The two oil majors have agreed in principle on the deal and
will sign an agreement shortly, Wednesday's Gulf News daily quoted
South Korean Ambassador to the United Arab Emirates (UAE) Kim
Song-Tuk as saying.
</P>
<P>
IPIC, owned by the Abu Dhabi government, will invest 500
million U.S. dollars in Hyundai Oil Refinery Co. as part of its
overseas investment strategy in the energy sector.
</P>
<P>
This is likely to be Abu Dhabi's first investment program in
South Korea's energy sector, Kim said.
</P>
<P>
Hyundai enjoys a refining capacity of 310,000 barrels per day.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a seminar on investment opportunities in South
Korea at the Abu Dhabi Chamber of Commerce and Industry, Kim said
bilateral trade between his country and the UAE slid to 3.6
billion dollars in 1998 from 4.5 billion dollars in the previous
year.
</P>
<P>
"The decline was mainly due to depressed oil prices," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, with the South Korean economy back on track, trade
with the UAE and some other countries will increase in 1999, he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
