<HEADLINE> S.Africa-Zimbabwe Trade Increases by 32% </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 28 (xinhua) -- Bilateral trade between South
Africa and Zimbabwe increased by 32.8 percent last year to 39.6
billion Zimbabwean dollars (over one billion U.S. dollars), the
daily Herald reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The figure excludes a substantial amount of undeclared and
informal trade between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Addressing guests at a reception to mark South Africa's fifth
independence anniversary in Harare Tuesday, acting South African
High Commissioner Hester Pretorious said despite the long
protracted dispute between the two countries over trade
imbalances, Zimbabwe still remained South Africa's number one
trading partner in Africa and 10th largest in the world.
</P>
<P>
"Our joint efforts to resolve our trade differences are
beginning to bear fruit and we are entering into a new phase in
our trade relations," she said.
</P>
<P>
In 1992, South Africa introduced punitive import duties of up
to 90 percent to protect its own clothing and textile industry at
a time when Zimbabwe was in the process of liberalizing its
economy. Since then, trade relations have been strained between
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the same occasion, Deputy Minister of Foreign
Affairs of Zimbabwe Nicholas Goche said although the current
trade between South Africa and Zimbabwe was being governed by the
1964 Trade Agreement, it was pleasing to note that progress had
been made in reaching an agreement on textiles and clothing and
agricultural products.
</P>
<P>
"We look forward to the acceleration of negotiations on and
agreement to cover such products as machinery, mechanical
suppliances and electrical equipment, " he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
