<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Needs $2 Billion to Eliminate Malaria: WHO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, April 28 (Xinhua) -- World Health Organization official
David Nabarro said here Tuesday that it will take two billion U.S.
dollars for the world to fight malaria in the next ten years, of
which 500 million dollars will be from his organization.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks at the on-going meeting on the elimination
of malaria in southern Africa, which has entered its second day.
</P>
<P>
A major challenge facing the world is to make remarkable
achievement in reducing the death rate of malaria and its
incidences before the year 2000, said the official.
</P>
<P>
WHO has pledged to increase fund for anti-malaria goods.
However, Nabarro said the wish could face difficulties due to poor
economic situation in sub-Saharan countries affected by the
disease.
</P>
<P>
He urged countries affected by malaria to try rely on
themselves in fighting the disease.
</P>
<P>
The four-day meeting which started Monday focus on the
effective elimination of malaria in Africa through strategies
closer to the African reality in accordance with the WHO Roll Back
Malaria program.
</P>
<P>
The Roll Back Malaria program which was initiated last year is
aimed at both eliminating malaria and supporting the development
of health systems in countries affected by this disease.
</P>
<P>
A WHO report showed that about 1.5 million to 2.7 million
people in the world die of malaria every year, among them at least
one million are children under five years.
</P>
<P>
Those affected by the disease are mainly living in countries
with poor health conditions, especially in sub-Saharan Africa,
which has brought negative impact on the countries' ecomony.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, to be closed Thursday, has drawn representatives
from South Africa, Angola, Botswana, Malawi, Namibia,
Swaziland,Zambia, Zimbabwe, Sao Tome &AMP; Principe and Seychelles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
