<HEADLINE> Electronic Trading Starts in Nigerian Stock Exchange </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian Stock Exchange
launched its Automated Trading System Tuesday, replacing the
manual call-over trading system after a one-week test run.
</P>
<P>
The new system is the final stage of a modernization program of
the stock market in Lagos which started in 1997 with the
introduction of a central clearing and depository system.
</P>
<P>
The launching of the new system was stalled by the soured
relations between Nigeria and Canada under the late dictator
General Sani Abacha as the Canadian experts handling the project
were denied Nigerian visas.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say the electronic trading will make the stock market
in the west African country more transparent and efficient, and it
is expected the new system would result in a quick release of
daily market summary of activities at the close of trading.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian stockbrokers who had a one-week rehearsal on the new
system welcomed the end of the noisy open outcry trading system
which had been in use since the market opened in 1961. 
</P>
</TEXT>
