<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: ABCs of Macao SAR Basic Law (57) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Can the Government of the MSAR Region negotiate and sign
agreements on mutual exemption of visas with foreign countries or
regions?
</P>
<P>
To facilitate the entry into and exit from their territory in
international contacts, many countries and regions have instituted
a visa system. However, to simplify the entry and exit procedures,
some countries or regions very often would sign bilateral or
multilateral agreements with other countries or regions to do away
with visa requirements for each other's citizens on the basis of
equality and reciprocity.
</P>
<P>
At present, residents in Macao are exempted from visa
requirements for entry into some countries with which Portugal has
signed such bilateral or multilateral agreements and made them
applicable to Macao. Likewise, citizens from the United States,
Germany, France and 30 or so other countries may enter Macao
without a visa according to the existing laws in Macao.
</P>
<P>
After Macao returns to China, the Government of MSAR may
exercise entry and exist control over entry into, stay in and exit
from Macao for people from foreign countries or regions.
</P>
<P>
As for visas, the Central Government will assist or authorize
the Government of the MSAR to negotiate and conclude the visa
abolition agreements with relevant foreign countries or regions.
In other words, with the assistance or authorization of the
Central Government, the Government of the MSAR definitely can
negotiate and sign such agreements with foreign countries and
regions on the basis of equality and reciprocity. This will make
it easier for Macao residents to go to foreign countries or
regions for work, study or as a tourist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990428.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: ABCs of Macao SAR Basic Law (58) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Can foreign governments set up consular missions in the MSAR?
</P>
<P>
According to Article 142 of the Basic Law, to facilitate the
development of economic and cultural relations between the MSAR
Region and foreign countries, foreign consular and other official
or semi-official missions may be set up in the MSAR, subject to
the approval of the Central Government.
</P>
<P>
Due to geographical reasons, no foreign government has set up
special consular mission in Macao. The consulates of more than 30
countries in Hong Kong concurrently handle consular affairs in
Macao.
</P>
<P>
Only a few countries have appointed some eminent figures in
Macao as their honorary consuls in Macao.
</P>
<P>
It is agreed between China and Portugal through consultations
that the Portuguese Government will set up a consular mission in
Macao before December 30, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Whether the foreign consular mission in Macao will remain will
be decided according to Article 142 of the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
The principles to be followed in handling this matter are:
</P>
<P>
1. Countries that have formal diplomatic relations with the
People's Republic of China and that have consular and other
official missions in Macao may maintain their missions there.
</P>
<P>
2. Countries that have not established formal diplomatic
relations with the People's Republic of China but have consular or
other official missions in Macao may either maintain them or
change them into semi-official missions in the light of the
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
3. Countries not recognized by the People's Republic of China
may only establish non-governmental institutions in the MSAR
Region.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990428.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
