<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Internet Service Provider Sees Good Days Ahead </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 28 (Xinhua) -- After years of a painful struggle
for survival, SOHU.com, one of the country's most successful
Internet service providers (ISP), is now looking for new expansion
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Chaoyang, founder and chief executive officer, has
attracted attention from representatives of foreign companies at
the China Business Summit of the World Economic Forum held in
China.
</P>
<P>
He said that his ISP company will balance its income and
spending within one or two years. The next step that the company
will take is to seek a merger or takeover by a major foreign
company so as to expand its operations.
</P>
<P>
China's ISP sector has gone through continuous consolidation in
the past five years. The number of ISPs in the country has
decreased from several hundred to scores. Most of the ISPs that
survived fierce competition are wholly or partially funded by
foreign companies. Over 90 percent of SOHU.com's capital is from
overseas investors.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said that foreign funds did not only ease the shortage of
funds of local ISPs, but also helped enhance their management
through strict requirements of economic returns from the overseas
investors.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the failure of most Chinese ISPs can be
attributed to a lack of market-oriented management mechanisms.
</P>
<P>
Zhang, a returned student from the United States, expressed
optimism about the future of ISPs in China.
</P>
<P>
"Faced with the same difficulties all Internet service
providers are competing as equals in the China market and only the
fittest can survive and win better returns than in any other
markets in the world," he said.
</P>
<P>
SOHU.com had one million US dollars in revenue last year,
becoming the best performing ISP in the country. Now it has about
one million pages downloaded from its website every day.
</P>
<P>
Zhang predicts that China's access to the world trade
organization will promote the expansion of his company.
</P>
<P>
"We have already established an advantage in the China market.
Increasing international competition will push our operations into
wider fields," he said.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1998, China had more than two million Internet
users. The figure is expected to grow to 3.5 million by the end of
this year and to 4.5 million by the end of 2000.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
