<HEADLINE> China to Start IP Phone Trial Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
 BEIJING, April 28 (Xinhua) -- China's Ministry of
Information Industry (MII) announced it has approved three Chinese
telecommunications service providers to conduct Internet Protocol
(IP) phone trial services.
</P>
<P>
The three companies are the China Telecommunications Corp. (
China Telecom), United Telecommunications Corp. (Unicom), and
China Jitong Telecommunications Co.
</P>
<P>
According to Chen Yin, an MII official in charge of telecom
development planning, China Telecom will launch its trial services
tomorrow, and the other two companies will start within the first
half of the year.
</P>
<P>
"The trial period is set to be six months and will conclude by
the end of the year," Chen said, adding that the official
operation of the IP phone services is expected to start then.
</P>
<P>
During the experimental period, international IP calls will be
charged at 4.8 yuan per minute, and domestic long-distance IP
calls will be charged for 0.3 yuan per minute.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the above charges, IP phone users will pay the
local call that is triggered by each IP call.
</P>
<P>
Regular DDD call in China is between 0.5 and one yuan per
minute. Regular IDD call within Asia except for the Middle East is
12 yuan per minute; that to other parts of the world is 15 yuan
per minute.
</P>
<P>
Li Lihua in charge of the telecom financial settlement of the
MII said the fee standard is a temporary one applicable only to
the trial period. Adjustments will be made before the official
full time service is introduced.
</P>
<P>
"The IP phone business is developed among three major telecom
outfit," Chen said, which is an "important step toward breaking
the monopoly and introducing competition in China's telecom
industry."
</P>
<P>
China Telecom will carry out experimental services in 25
cities, and the other two will handle a further 12 cities.
</P>
<P>
The MII also pledged to continue to crack down on illegal IP
phone services to ensure a "healthy and orderly" development of
the telecom market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
