<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: U.S. Press Criticizes NATO's Strategy and Bombing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The North Atlantic Treaty
Organization's new "strategic concept" adopted by NATO leaders at
the just-concluded summit and the continued air strikes against
Yugoslavia were heavily condemned by the United States press
recently.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post, in a signed article, described the
alliance as "an idea whose time has passed". It said that the
conflict in Kosovo has shown that NATO is "increasingly irrelevant
to contemporary problems".
</P>
<P>
The article said that the alliance "has little to celebrate"
for its 50th anniversary, since it lost its raison d'etre after
the end of the Cold War. "America's European partners no longer
needed our protection, because there was no external enemy to
contain," it added.
</P>
<P>
NATO adopted the new "strategic concept" at the summit held
here over the weekend, which shifted its primary task from
deterring external attack to preventing terrorism, ethnic conflict
and other low-level security threats.
</P>
<P>
"This step transformed NATO from a coherent and credible
defense pact to a vague and loosely defined regional militia," the
article said.
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles Times also published readers' letters on Tuesday,
criticizing NATO's new strategy and air bombing in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
"In a major political blunder, the U.S.-led NATO decision to
bomb Yugoslavia is turning a low-level conflict into a nightmare
of biblical proportions," one of the letters said, adding that "
the bombing is a blatant violation of international law".
</P>
<P>
The bombing is "destroying a major European city and creating
serious environmental problems", and "ruining relations with
Russia", the letter said.
</P>
<P>
It called for a halt to the bombing and a start of honest talks
before the tragedy escsalated into "a major European war -- or
worse".
</P>
<P>
Another letter that appeared in the same newspaper pointed out
that NATO had been used "to justify trillions of dollars of
totally useless military spending both here and abroad", and it
had put off the establishment of democracy "in Eastern Europe and
elsewhere for decades" by promoting military confrontation.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Times, in a strong-worded advertisement by the
Milica Rakic Memorial Committee on Tuesday, called passionately
for a stop to the air assault in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
"We are deeply saddened by the swiftly worsening situation in
Serbia (Yugoslavia). NATO bombing and missile strikes only
aggravate the danger," it said.
</P>
<P>
The advertisement said that the U.S. involvement in a Balkan
conflict "has led to more refugees, more destruction and more loss
of human life".
</P>
<P>
"We are guilty of aggression against a nation that has done
nothing against another country. We have set a precedent that
would-be-aggressors can use to justify attacks against other
countries," it said.
</P>
<P>
The advertisement condemned the U.S. government for aping "
dictators who violated treaties and other solemn agreements".
</P>
<P>
"The U.N. considers the bombing of Yugoslavia illegal. People
here and abroad deplore NATO's use of force to achieve a political
settlement. In addition, we conveniently ignored the International
Convention of Treaties (1980), which asserts that agreements
resulting from coercion and the use of force are invalid," it said.
</P>
<P>
The advertisement urged the government to learn from "the
horrendous experience of Vietnam", and stressed that "war is no
solution in the Balkans". 
</P>
</TEXT>
