<HEADLINE> Mexican President Starts Visit to Brazil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Mexican President Ernesto
Zedillo started his first two-day official visit to Brazil on
Tuesday in order to secure stronger ties between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The president was received by Brazilian Foreign Minister Luiz
Felipe Lampreia in the military base near the international
airport of Juselino Jubistscheck.
</P>
<P>
Zedillo visited Brazil, Mexico's biggest trade partner in Latin
America, in the backdrop that the Brazilian government has refused
on various occasions to sign a bilateral trade agreement with his
country.
</P>
<P>
Trade between Mexico and Brazil last year reached 1.57 billion
U.S. dollars, bringing Brazil, the South American giant, a surplus
of 501 million dollars, but fell by 17 percent in January this
year compared with the same month in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
