<DOCNO> XIE19990428.0260 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> International Institutions Agree to Help Balkan States </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Officials from international
financial institutions and donor countries Tuesday night agreed to
address the devastating economic effects of the Kosovo war on
neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
Officials from 33 countries and representatives from the World
Bank, the International Monetary Fund (IMF), the United Nations
Human Rights Commission, the European Investment Bank and other
institutions reached an agreement after a meeting.
</P>
<P>
They said in a joint statement that neighboring countries would
need "a swift donor response ...to help meet the severe
humanitarian and other financial needs" caused by a wave of
refugees who have streamed out of Kosovo, since NATO started
airstrikes against Yugoslavia on March 24.
</P>
<P>
The countries will need billions of dollars in aid to deal with
the problems, a joint report from the World Bank and International
Monetary Fund said.
</P>
<P>
The costs of humanitarian aid alone could reach upward of 300
million U.S. dollars if the bombing drags on through 1999, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
The aid, if provided, did not include the cost of resettling
refugees or rebuilding Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
"The crisis in Kosovo is real," World Bank President James
Wolfensohn told reporters. "It's not just Kosovo and the Yugoslav
Republic, but also adjacent states."
</P>
<P>
The report studied the effects on six neighboring countries to
Yugoslavia. They are Albania, Bosnia and Herzegovina, Bulgaria,
Croatia, Macedonia and Romania.
</P>
<P>
It emphasized that the strains of providing for destitute
refugees would be great, especially since the countries most
affected, Albania and Macedonia, are poor.
</P>
<P>
"As the refugees have, by and large, been stripped of their
possessions and savings, they are reliant on others --
humanitarian organizations, local residents, recipient country
governments -- to provide for their basic needs," the draft report
said.
</P>
<P>
The report looked at two scenarios. Under one of them, the
conflict in Kosovo is resolved quickly and official trade with the
Yugoslav Republic begins to return toward its pre-crisis level
later this year.
</P>
<P>
The financing need was based on an assumption of an influx of
more than 250,000 refugees to the affected countries.
</P>
<P>
The other scenario involves a war lasting throughout the year,
with all official trade with Yugoslavia assumed to be suspended.
That scenario assumes the number of refugees peaks toward the
middle of 1999 at about 750,000.
</P>
<P>
In addition to more than 300 million dollars in aid needed, the
costs would produce a balance of payments gap of 1.5 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
That means the total cost for providing for refugees would hit
1.8 billion dollars, or about 2.5 percent of the region's GDP.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
