<HEADLINE> Xinhua Economic News Summary at 0530 GMT, April 28 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- China called here Tuesday for joint efforts of
the international community to resolve financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
"With increased economic globalization and financial
integration, and growing interdependence among different economies,
the ultimate resolution of crisis depends on the joint efforts of
the international community," said Liu Mingkang, Deputy Governor
of People's Bank of China. (US-China)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW YORK -- Wall Street stocks ended mixed Tuesday with the Dow
Jones industrial average rising into record territory and the
technology heavy Nasdaq index falling.
</P>
<P>
The Dow closed up 113.12 at the record high of 10,831.71 as AT&AMP;
T and DuPont, both Dow components, reported strong earnings in the
first quarter of this year. AT&AMP;T gained 61 cents a share, beating
the expectation of 57 cents while DuPont got 66 cents a share,
beating analysts' expected 60 cents. (US-Wall Street)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
HOHHOT -- China and Japan have cooperated in carrying out a
five-year research and training program in the dairy products
sector in north China's Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The program, which was recently approved by a group of Chinese
and Japanese specialists, was designed to improve Inner Mongolia's
research into dairy products and the capacity to develop new dairy
products. (China-Japan)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MANILA -- The Trade Union Congress of the Philippines (TUCP)
will formally ask the regional wage and productivity boards of
Metro Manila and Cebu to increase minimum wages, Business World
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
TUCP spokesman Alex Aguilar was quoted by the newspaper as
saying Tuesday that the formal petitions will be filed with the
Metro Manila and Cebu wage boards next week, seeking 45 peso (1.
125 U.S. dollars) to 55 peso (1.375 U.S. dollars) and 60 peso (1.5
U.S. dollars) basic wage increases, respectively. (Philippines-
Metro Manila)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BANGKOK -- Investors are regaining confidence in Thailand with
225 projects applying for promotional privileges in the first
quarter of this year, the first time the number has increased in
two years, according to Chakramon Phasukvanich, deputy secretary-
general of the Board of Investment of the Thai government.
</P>
<P>
The total is almost 15 more than the first quarter of 1998,
when 196 applications were filed. (Thailand-Investment)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BANGKOK -- Thailand's gem and jewelry shipments in January and
February of this year totaled 7.3 billion baht (197 million U.S.
dollars), down by 36 percent from 11.54 billion baht (311 million
U.S. dollars) in the same period last year, according to the
Export Promotion Department of the Thai government.
</P>
<P>
Strong competition from India, as well as sluggish demand in
the United States, Europe and Japan were mainly to blame for the
sharp decline, said Sanit Vorapanya, director-general of the
department. (Thailand-Gem) 
</P>
