<HEADLINE> China Seeks Cooperation in Fighting Cross-Border Crime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- China on Tuesday told a United
Nations (UN) conference on preventing crime that more
international cooperation was needed to fight transnational
organized crime.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Yishan, head of the Chinese delegation and China's
ambassador to the U.N. in Vienna, said that stronger international
links -- based on mutual respect for sovereignty, equality, and
mutual benefit -- were in the best interests of every country.
</P>
<P>
The international community had to urgently toughen its actions
against cross-border organized crime which in recent years has
grown considerably and has done grave harm to social order and
international trading and economic activities, he noted.
</P>
<P>
China, also facing such crime during the process of opening to
the outside world, was paying great attention to expanding
judicial cooperation with other states, while intensifying
operations against criminal activities, he stressed. China called
on the international community to conclude a treaty on a full-
scale fight against cross-border organized crime as soon as
possible.
</P>
<P>
The conference will end on May 6. 
</P>
</TEXT>
