<HEADLINE> Mexico, Brazil to Promote Bilateral Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Brazilian President Fernando
Henrique Cardoso and visiting Mexican counterpart Ernesto Zedillo
signed an agreement on Tuesday for the creation of a Brazil-Mexico
Commission for the 21st century to strengthen cooperation between
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents agreed that trade ministers from the two
countries should begin talks on preferential tariffs, which failed
to be agreed in December 1997.
</P>
<P>
Cardoso and Zedillo noted that they will try to stimulate a "
frank and open dialogue" among member countries of the Rio Group
during in its summit meeting on May 28 and 29 in Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents will also attend negotiations for the
formation of the Free Trade Area of the Americas (FTAA), with the
intention of progressively eliminating the barriers to trade and
the investment in the American continent.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Brazil's exports to Mexico were over one billion U.S.
dollars, while its imports from Mexico stood at 974 million
dollars, with a trade surplus of 28 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
