<HEADLINE> Investment in Thailand Up for 1st Time in 2 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Investors are regaining
confidence in Thailand with 225 projects applying for promotional
privileges in the first quarter of this year, the first time the
number has increased in two years, according to Chakramon
Phasukvanich, deputy secretary-general of the Board of Investment
of the Thai government.
</P>
<P>
The total is almost 15 more than the first quarter of 1998,
when 196 applications were filed.
</P>
<P>
Of the 225 projects, 174 are foreign owned and 51 are Thai
ventures.
</P>
<P>
In terms of investment, the proposals total 46.7 billion baht
(1.26 billion U.S. dollars), up 17 percent from the same period
last year.
</P>
<P>
The figures showed the business climate was promising,
Chakramon was quoted Wednesday by the Bangkok Post as saying.
</P>
<P>
Japanese led the foreign contingent with 48 projects worth a
total of 16.8 billion baht (454 million U.S. dollars), followed by
Taiwanese, 31 projects worth 4.2 billion baht (113 million U.S.
dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
