<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Government Ready For Talks With Tamil Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lanka government is ready
for peace talks with the Tamil rebels if they give up their demand
for a separate state and conclude the talks within a given time
frame.
</P>
<P>
President Chandrika Kumaratunga Monday reiterated this when the
Religious Alliance for Peace, which undertook a peace mission to
northern Sri Lanka Monday, met her here and briefed her on the
outcome of its mission, the official Daily News Wednesday
reported.
</P>
<P>
The religious leaders explained to the president the
difficulties of Tamil civilians and requested her to supply them
with basic needs which she agreed to do, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
She said the government had despatched essential food and other
items to the areas mentioned but the Tamil rebels prevented those
goods from reaching the innocent civilians.
</P>
<P>
The president pointed out that since she assumed office, she
had exchanged 43 letters with the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam
(LTTE) in an effort to restore peace.
</P>
<P>
But when the government formulated a 40 billion rupee (About
600 million U.S. dollars) program for the rehabilitation of the
north and requested the LTTE cooperation towards its
implementation, they wanted the withdrawal of the government
troops from the north and east if they were to cooperate.
</P>
<P>
The president said she was not prepared to make the mistakes of
the former government.
</P>
<P>
At the end of last year, the president said her government
would like to continue peace talks with the LTTE.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after coming to power in 1994, the government opened
talks with the LTTE rebels who have been fighting a war for a
separate state in the country since 1983, but the LTTE abruptly
pulled out to resume their protracted campaign in April 1995.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
