<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand's Gems, Jewellery Shipments Decline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's gem and jewellery
shipments in January and February of this year totaled 7.3 billion
baht (197 million U.S. dollars), down by 36 percent from 11.54
billion baht (311 million U.S. dollars) in the same period last
year, according to the Export Promotion Department of the Thai
government.
</P>
<P>
Strong competition from India, as well as sluggish demand in
the United States, Europe and Japan were mainly to blame for the
sharp decline, said Sanit Vorapanya, director-general of the
department.
</P>
<P>
Exports of diamonds dropped to 1.98 billion baht (53.5 million
U.S. dollars) in the two-month period, down by 23 percent from 2.6
billion baht (70.2 million U.S. dollars) a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
Gemstones and pearls earned 1.4 billion baht (37.8 million U.S.
dollars), down from two billion baht (54 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Jewellery exports were worth 3.5 billion baht (94.5 million
U.S. dollars), down by 50 percent from 6.9 billion baht (186
million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Major importers of Thai gems and jewellery in the first two
months of this year were the United States, Japan, Israel and
Belgium. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990428.0283 </DOCNO>
