<HEADLINE> Italy Pushes for Rapid Progress in Mideast Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto
Dini told his visiting Israeli counterpart that only rapid
progress in the Middle East peace process would stop the world
thinking that the blockage was on the Israeli side.
</P>
<P>
Meeting Israeli Foreign Minister Ariel Sharon here on Tuesday,
Dini spoke of the need for "positive developments to sweep away
the impression that most of the obstacles come from Israel."
</P>
<P>
He also recalled that at the March 24 European Union (EU)
summit in Berlin, the 15 member countries reaffirmed their view
that the Palestinians had a right to self-determination and their
readiness to recognize a Palestinian state at the appropriate time.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian President Yasser Arafat said he would declare an
independent state for his people as of next month with or without
Israeli consent.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers' talks also focused on bilateral relations,
the euro-Mediterranean partnership and the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
Their meeting came a day after United States President Bill
Clinton said he would send a letter to Arafat spelling out
Washington's position regarding "the right of Palestinians to live
freely on their own soil."
</P>
<P>
Clinton made it clear however that U.S. support for a
Palestinian state was conditional on the continuation of
negotiations with Israel for another year. This would mean Arafat
would have to put off his declaration of independence, originally
planned for May 4, until 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
