<HEADLINE> First Quarter Sees Dropping Price in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 28 (Xinhua) -- A buyer's market was prominent in
China in the first quarter of this year, a senior official said
here today.
</P>
<P>
Ding Junfa, deputy director of the State Administration of
Internal Trade, told a press conference that the oversupply of
commodities resulted in a 2.9 percent drop in the national's
retail price index in the first quarter from the same period last
year.
</P>
<P>
He said the consumer price index fell by 1.4 percent during
that period. The average price of industrial products dropped by 5.
9 percent and that of raw materials by 6.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
Statistics released by the All-China Commercial Information
Center show that of the 606 major commodities, 98.3 percent are
expected to be in excessive supply in the first half of the year.
</P>
<P>
Of the industrial consumer goods, 87.2 percent will be in
oversupply. Major farm and sideline products are expected to be in
more excessive supply, according to the statistics.
</P>
<P>
Ding pointed to the slumping pig price resulting from increased
output and sluggish demand. He called for measures to be adopted
to halt the drop in the pig price.  
</P>
</TEXT>
