<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia Suffers Heavy Civilian Casualties, Damage: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, April 27 (Xinhua) -- More than 400 Serbian civilians
have been killed and over 4,000 injured since NATO launched
airstrikes against Yugoslavia on March 24, Serbian Health Minister
Leposava Milicevic told a press conference here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Around 30 hospitals in Belgrade, Pristina, Kragujevac, Kraljevo,
Novi Sad, Nis and Cacak and some major highways and bridges were
bombed by NATO airplanes, which made it more difficult to
transport and treat the wounded, said Milicevic.
</P>
<P>
According to another senior official in the Health Department,
NATO's wanton and indiscriminate bombing of Yugoslav chemical
factories, refineries and oil depots has caused the leaking of a
large amount of poisonous materials and severely threatened the
life of the people. The conduct in its nature is no better than
using chemical weapons, he added.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslav experts are now studying all measures to minimize the
possible harm to residents' health caused by those materials.
</P>
