<HEADLINE> Slaney's Medal Stripped of by IAAF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Mary Slaney of the United
States, the former world champion in the women's 1,500 and 3,000
meters, is going ahead with a lawsuit against the international
athletics governing body IAAF despite Monday's ruling by an
arbitration panel that she failed a drug test three years ago.
</P>
<P>
"They think they are protected over there, safe in their little
cocoon," Slaney said, refering to the IAAF headquarters in Monte
Carlo. "They can take away whatever rights the athletes had. This
has to be addressed, fought and changed."
</P>
<P>
Slaney's lawyer said he doubts the suit ever will go to trial
becuase the IAAF would prefer a settlement rather than make public
what he called a "sham" test for female athletes.
</P>
<P>
"We're going to take the veil from over how they've been
operating their doping program. We're going to find out what
athletes they've investigated, which athletes they've let off and
why, to show the whole thing is a sham," attorney Jim Coleman said.
"It's fraudulent, and we are going to prove it."
</P>
<P>
The suit seeks unspecified damages and also names the U.S.
Olympic Committee, which administered the test Slaney failed
during the 1996 Olympic Trials. 
</P>
