<HEADLINE> WNBA, Union Back at Bargaining Table </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The WNBA sides returned to the
bargaining table Tuesday in an effort to settle down the labor
dispute in New York.
</P>
<P>
The sides talked for eight hours Monday, trying to resolve
differences which caused an apparent agreement to fall apart last
week.
</P>
<P>
The league postponed its player draft which had been scheduled
for Tuesday, causing the WNBA players association to issue a
statement charging league officials with trying to intimidate the
players.
</P>
<P>
The three-month season is supposed to begin on June 10.
</P>
<P>
The union claimed that the league introduced five issues in
talks last Wednesday night and said that if the players
association did not agree to them, there would be no deal.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the union and league agreed on a four-year deal that
would increase minimum salaries from 15,000 U.S. dollars to 30,000
foro veterans and 25,000 for rookies.
</P>
<P>
Those figures would increase to 40,000 and 30,000 respectively
by 2002.
</P>
<P>
The two-year-old WNBA has added expansion teams in Orlando and
Minnesota for this season and plans to add four more cities by
2000. 
