<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The Trade Union Congress of the
Philippines (TUCP) will formally ask the regional wage and
productivity boards of Metro Manila and Cebu to increase minimum
wages, Business World reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
TUCP spokesman Alex Aguilar was quoted by the newspaper as
saying Tuesday that the formal petitions will be filed with the
Metro Manila and Cebu wage boards next week, seeking 45 peso
(1.125 U.S. dollars) to 55 peso (1.375 U.S. dollars) and 60 peso
(1.5 U.S. dollars) basic wage increases, respectively.
</P>
<P>
The TUCP is one of the country's oldest and largest labor
federations with an estimated membership of two million
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
Aguilar said the statements of President Joseph Estrada which
tend to indicate the administration is open to the possibility of
a wage increase encouraged TUCP to proceed with its petitions.
</P>
<P>
"When President Estrada said the government was studying the
possibility of granting a minimum wage increase this year, we took
this as a sign that the economy may be capable again of supporting
another round of increases and it was time to file our petition,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Executive Secretary Ranaldo Zamora reiterated the
Presidential Palace has no plan to order an across-the-board wage
hike and will instead let the regional wage boards to decide
whether or not local conditions warrant an adjustment.
</P>
<P>
Zamora said President Estrada has directed the Departments of
Labor and Employment and of Trade and Industry to convene the
regional wage boards and decide on the matter, adding that the
Presidential Palace does see a need to increase the daily minimum
wage in some regions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
