<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 300-Meter Long Painting on Ancient Chinese Emperors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, April 28 (Xinhua) -- A young artist in north China's
Shanxi Province has drawn a 300-meter long painting featuring
ancient emperors in 5,000 years of Chinese history.
</P>
<P>
Over the past ten year from December 1987 to October 1998, Zhao
Kailei, the painter, used his brush to draw a total of 102
emperors on a scroll that is 1.94 meters high and weighs 150 kg.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the painting also describes distinguished
officials, related historical events and battles including over 20,
000 persons.
</P>
<P>
Zhao referred to large numbers of documents, historic works and
archaeological discoveries. He visited cultural relics and sites
across the country for art clues in his painting.
</P>
<P>
His painting combines the tradition of the Chinese realistic
painting skill, which is characterized by fine brushwork and close
attention to details, with the use of skill on light and color in
Western paintings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
