<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Enterprises Urged to Improve Safety Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 28 (Xinhua) -- More than 100,000 Chinese people
were killed in industrial, mining and traffic accidents last year,
according to figures released by the State Economic and Trade
Commission (SETC).
</P>
<P>
The SETC urged Chinese enterprises "to give top priority to
safety while striving to improve economic efficiency."
</P>
<P>
According to a SETC document quoted by today's China Daily, the
death toll of accidents dropped in 1998 over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Industrial and mining accidents dropped 16.63 percent to an
aggregate 15,372 in 1998, with the death toll hitting 14,660.
</P>
<P>
Non-mining firms recorded 5,439 deaths from accidents, down 13.
57 percent from 1997.
</P>
<P>
Traffic accidents shot up 13.8 percent on a year-on-year basis
to 346,129 in 1998, killing 78,067 people.
</P>
<P>
According to the document, private enterprises have the most
serious problem of ignoring the importance of safety. These
enterprises lack safety consciousness and sufficient investment in
safety facilities.
</P>
<P>
Driving at excessive speeds and drivers with less than three
years' driving experience are the main culprits for the high death
toll in traffic accidents, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
