<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar's Private Industrial Enterprises Reach Over 36,000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Private industrial enterprises
registered in Myanmar reached a total of 36,275 at the end of
1998, according to the latest issue of the local Myanmar Business
News.
</P>
<P>
Of the industrial enterprises, 4,075 are medium-sized
businesses and 30,650 small-sized businesses.
</P>
<P>
Of these, 7,980 are located in Mandalay, topping all other
states and divisions, followed by Yangon with 5,396 and Bago with
4,514.
</P>
<P>
According to official figures, in fiscal 1997-98, Myanmar's
private sector contributed 75.4 percent to gross domestic product.
The sector took up 67.8 percent of the total export value, while
representing 71.9 percent of the total import.
</P>
<P>
The output, export and import value of Myanmar's private sector
increased by 6.8 percent, 21.5 percent and 31.2 percent
respectively as compared with 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, Myanmar began implementing a privatization plan,
leasing out some state-owned small, medium and large economic
enterprises to private entrepreneurs who have technical skills,
sound management and strong financial backing.
</P>
<P>
With the passage of time, the output, export and import value
of Myanmar's private sector are expected to rise further.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
