<HEADLINE> China, EU Resume Group Talks for Third Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 28 (Xinhua)-- China and the European Union (EU)
resumed group talks on China's entry into the World Trade
Organization (WTO) for the third day at 9:40 here on Wednesday
morning.
</P>
<P>
The talks are being held in two groups, one on the tariffs on
goods trade, and the other on service trade, according to a source
at the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation (MOFTEC).
</P>
<P>
Seven members of the EU delegation participated in Wednesday's
group talks.
</P>
<P>
The current round of talks between China and the EU started
here Monday morning, before negotiations between China and the U.S.
on the remaining issues concerning China's accession to the WTO
concluded. The China-EU talks are expected to last for one week.
</P>
<P>
Long Yongtu, chief representative of negotiation of the MOFTEC,
told Xinhua Monday that China is prepared to make the "utmost
efforts" to push forward negotiations with the EU and will strive
to achieve important progress as soon as possible after he met
Gerard Depayre, deputy director-general of Directorate General 1
of EC.
</P>
<P>
According to the top Chinese negotiator, the European side has
expressed "firm support" for China's entry into WTO within the
year 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
