<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Sino-British Effort to Prevent Hemophilia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The British Federation of
Hemophilia and the Anhui Hemophilia Center in east China's Anhui
Province have decided to work together to try and find an
effective treatment for hemophilia, a hereditary disease that at
present cannot be cured.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from the two institutions have signed an
agreement here which will see them work on a series of research
projects in the coming years.
</P>
<P>
This is the first joint effort by Chinese and British
researchers to tackle this particular disease.
</P>
<P>
A group of researchers from both institutions will center on
exploring genetic and antenatal diagnosis in a bid to find a more
efficient way to check out the disease at an early stage.
</P>
<P>
Another related project due to start soon is the prevention of
different types of hemophilia.
</P>
<P>
Hemophilia is a condition in which one of the normal blood-
clotting factors is absent, causing prolonged bleeding from even
minor cuts and injuries.
</P>
<P>
Medical data show that five out of every 100,000 people
worldwide suffer from the disease. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
