<HEADLINE> Man United Deny Ajax Keeper Move </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 27 (Xinhua) -- English Premier League football
club Manchester United have rubbished claims by the Dutch
international Edwin Van der Sar that they have approached about a
summer move to Old Trafford.
</P>
<P>
The Ajax goalkeeper said Manchester United want him to replace
Peter Schmeichel but United boss Alex Ferguson said he is talking
"nonsense", according to the BBC reports on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The club have been linked with a number of replacements for the
departing Dane including Aston Villa's Mark Bosnich and Ipswich's
England Under-21 keeper Richard Wright, but Van der Sar says he is
top of the list.
</P>
<P>
"Manchester United were in contact with me to ask about my
feelings and availability about joining them if a transfer could
be agreed between the clubs," the 28-year-old told the Daily Mail.
</P>
<P>
"Obviously I have to be interested," added the five million
pounds rated player.
</P>
<P>
Ferguson has denied making any approach but revealed he has a
very short list of two possible replacements.
</P>
<P>
"I've not made my mind up about a goalkeeper, although there
are two we're thinking about," said Ferguson.
</P>
<P>
He would not reveal the identities of his targets, but appeared
confident of successfully signing one of them.
</P>
<P>
"When the time comes to announce a goalkeeping replacement, we
will announce it," he added.
</P>
<P>
Van der Sar is thought to be keener to accept United's strict
pay scale which rises to a maximum of 25,000 pounds per week.
</P>
<P>
The Dutchman realises he would make a great deal more than that
from sponsorship deals and endorsements. 
</P>
</TEXT>
