<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Service Sector Makes Half of Guangzhou's Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The service sector has risen to
make up the largest proportion in the economy of this capital of
south China's Guangdong Province, a showcase of the country's
market economy reforms.
</P>
<P>
The latest official statistics show that the service sector
accounted for 50.9 percent of Guangzhou's gross domestic product
in 1998, up from 29.7 percent in 1978, when it launched its
opening-up and market economy reform drive.
</P>
<P>
The service sector has become a pacesetter in Guangzhou's
economic development, with rapidest growth rates reported in the
areas of banking, insurance, transportation, communications and
product distribution, a city official said.
</P>
<P>
For instance, Guangzhou had 2,813 banks and bank subsidiaries
by the end of 1998, 27.6 times the figure for 1978. Meanwhile,
overseas banking and insurance institutions have set up 62
operational agencies in Guangzhou.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics also show that Guangzhou's retail sales of
consumer goods totaled 90.45 billion yuan (10.9 billion US dollars)
last year, a surge of 46.1 times over the figure for 1978. The per
capita consumption volume was the highest among China's ten
biggest cities.
</P>
<P>
Guangzhou's telecommunications and real estate sector are also
among the most developed in China, according to official data.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
