<DOCNO> XIE19990428.0327 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Maps Showing Evidence of Japanese Aggression </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The two maps discovered last year
in Xuzhou, a major city in east China's Jiangsu Province, have
been confirmed to be special ordnance surveys used by Japanese
aggressors when occupying the city in the 1940s.
</P>
<P>
The maps, published in January 1941 by a Japanese news agency,
trace Japanese military bases, as well as local banks, schools,
shops and other facilities in Xuzhou.
</P>
<P>
One of them, the New Greater Xuzhou Map, contains detailed
descriptions of Xuzhou's topography, population, streets, news
agencies, as well as key industries.
</P>
<P>
Researchers with the city archives say the maps reveal the fact
that Xuzhou was one of the pivotal Chinese cities in Japan's plan
of occupation.
</P>
<P>
According to other records, including those made by the
Japanese, at least 300,000 Chinese were butchered and more than 20,
000 women raped in December of 1937 in Nanjing, the provincial
capital, by Japanese invaders.
</P>
<P>
Also known as "the Rape of Nanking (Nanjing)", the Nanjing
Massacre was later described as "a dark page in modern human
civilization" by historians worldwide.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
