<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, April 28 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton proposed gun-control
legislation Tuesday to raise the legal age for handgun possession
from 18 to 21 and hold negligent parents liable when their
children commit crimes with guns.
</P>
<P>
Buyers of explosives would also be subject to the same Brady
law background checks as gun purchasers. (US-Clinton-Gun-control
measures)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- the United States is preparing a comprehensive
embargo on all exports to Serbia, including oil and other
petroleum products but excluding humanitarian supplies, the State
Department said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"We are now working through the amendment to the export
administration regulations that are pending -- which would
establish a comprehensive embargo on exports and re-exports to
Serbia of all goods," State Department spokesman James Rubin told
reporters. (US-Serbia)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TIRANA -- Albania claimed Tuesday that Serb forces in Kosovo
continued artillery attack at two border villages in northern
Albania.
</P>
<P>
At about 18:00 p.m. local time (1600 GMT) Tuesday, Serb
soldiers bombarded the villages of Padesh and Kamenice in Tropoja
district with 82 mm mortars and 120 mm cannons, the police chief
of the district, Muharrem Gjuriqi, was quoted as saying.  (
Albania-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ATHENS -- Greek Foreign Minister George Papandreou will leave
here for Moscow Wednesday to hold talks with his Russian
counterpart, Igor Ivanov, as part of Greece's efforts to seek a
political solution to the Yugoslav crisis.
</P>
<P>
Papandreou would also meet U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan,
whose presence in Moscow was a fortunate coincidence which would
enable Athens and Moscow to make efforts jointly with the U.N.
towards finding a political settlement, Greek government spokesman
Dimitris Reppas said at a press briefing. (Greece-Russia)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States is willing to take part in
organizing a referendum on autonomy in East Timor in August, a
State Department official said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The official's remarks came as Indonesian President B.J.
Habibie announced after talks with Australian Prime Minister John
Howard earlier on Tuesday that he had accepted all of a U.N. draft
on the referendum arrangements "without any changes." (US-East
Timor)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States said Tuesday that the alliance
remains prepared to "pause" its month-long bombing of Yugoslavia
if there is a "demonstrable and verifiable commitment implemented"
of Serb troop withdrawal from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
However, State Department spokesman James Rubin said the air
strikes would be resumed if Belgrade reneged on its commitment. (
US-Yugoslavia) 
</P>
