<HEADLINE> China, Japan Cooperate in Dairy Products Research </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, April 28 (Xinhua) -- China and Japan have cooperated in
carrying out a five-year research and training program in the
dairy products sector in north China's Inner Mongolia Autonomous
Region.
</P>
<P>
The program, which was recently approved by a group of Chinese
and Japanese specialists, was designed to improve Inner Mongolia's
research into dairy products and the capacity to develop new dairy
products.
</P>
<P>
Forty Japanese experts were sent to work at Inner Mongolia's
Dairy Products Research and Training Center, which was specially
built for the implementation of the program. Twenty five young
and middle aged technical workers from Inner Mongolia were sent to
Japan to receive training under the program.
</P>
<P>
In the past five years experts from both sides collected,
separated, appraised and stored a great number of healthy
microorganisms, and set up four experimental production lines at
the center for pasteurized milk, ice cream, butter and condensed
milk.
</P>
<P>
They developed and made pasteurized milk, ice cream and yogurt
which were all selling well on the market, according to an
official of the center.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese Government provided the program with 500 million
Japanese yen (about four million U.S dollars) of free aid via
Japan's International Cooperation Agency (JICA), said the official.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
