<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> O'Sullivan, Williams on Brink of Semis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Ronnie O'Sullivan and Mark
Williams were both on brink of semi-final berths at the World
Snooker Championships in Sheffield, England on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
World number three O'Sullivan led 1991 champion John Parrott 11-
5 while Welshman Williams led Ireland's Ken Doherty, finalist for
the last two years, by the same score in the quarter-finals.
</P>
<P>
O'Sullivan, looking on course for his third semifinal
appearance, made two century breaks, wasting a chance to compile a
maximum 147 when he missed a black after potting 14 reds and 13
blacks with the colours well placed.
</P>
<P>
Williams dropped the first frame against Doherty but claimed
the next eight before the Irishman rallied and cut the lead to 9-5.
</P>
<P>
Williams, beaten by Doherty in last year's semifinals, won the
last two frames of the evening to gain a six-frame cushion at 11-5.
</P>
<P>
Doherty's hopes of reaching the final for the third year
running now hinge on whether he can reproduce the sort of comeback
he made to beat Nigel Bond in the second round.
</P>
<P>
Defending champion John Higgins was in superb form in the
opening session of his quarter-final tie against Stephen Lee.
</P>
<P>
Higgins made a second frame clearance of 132 on his way to
establishing a 4-0 interval lead over Lee, who is making his first
quarter-final appearance at the Crucible.
</P>
<P>
Higgins continued in similar vein at the resumption of play,
compiling four half-century breaks to end the session with a
commanding lead of 8-0.
</P>
<P>
Stephen Hendry, seeking a record seventh world title,
established a four-frame lead over Welsh qualifier Matthew Stevens.
</P>
<P>
Hendry has yet to notch a century in the tournament but he gave
Stevens few chances to settle into his rhythm, opening up a lead
of 4-0.
</P>
<P>
Stevens reduced Hendry's lead to 5-2 with a 100 break but
Hendry won the last frame of the session to end 6-2 ahead.
</P>
</TEXT>
