<HEADLINE> US Sees no Early Breakthrough in Kosovo Diplomacy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The United States said Tuesday
that the alliance remains prepared to "pause" its month-long
bombing of Yugoslavia if there is a "demonstrable and verifiable
commitment implemented" of Serb troop withdrawal from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
However, State Department spokesman James Rubin said the air
strikes would be resumed if Belgrade reneged on its commitment.
</P>
<P>
Rubin insisted "there is no compromise" on the alliance's
primary objectives.
</P>
<P>
In Moscow, U.S. Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott held
two two-hour meetings in Moscow with Russian Foreign Minister Igor
Ivanov and former Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin, now Russia's
special envoy on Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Talbott made the trip to try to narrow differences between the
United States and Russia on Kosovo and to ensure relations between
these two nuclear powers are not destroyed by the conflict.
</P>
<P>
Rubin called the Moscow meetings "constructive", he said,
adding that the issue of NATO's new oil embargo against Yugoslavia
did not figure prominently in Talbott's talks.
</P>
<P>
"We have received assurances from the highest levels of the
Russian government over the weekend and in regular conversations
between Foreign Minister Ivanov and the secretary (of State
Madeleine Albright) that they do not want to enter this conflict,"
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
