<DOCNO> XIE19990428.0347 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Balkan Need Billion Dollars for Refugees Fleeing Bombing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Balkan countries will need
billions of dollars in aid to deal with the problems caused by a
tidal wave of refugees because of NATO bombing in Kosovo, a draft
joint report from the World Bank and International Monetary Fund
said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The costs of humanitarian aid alone could reach upward of
$300 million if the bombing drags on through 1999, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The aid, if provided, did not include the cost of resettling
refugees or rebuilding Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
"The crisis in Kosovo is real," World Bank President James
Wolfensohn told reporters. "It's not just Kosovo and the
Yugoslav Republic, but also adjacent states."
</P>
<P>
The draft report studied the effects on six neighboring
countries to Yugoslavia. They are Albania, Bosnia and
Herzegovina, Bulgaria, Croatia, Macedonian and Romania.
</P>
<P>
The report emphasized that the strains of providing for
destitute refugees would be great, especially since the
countries most affected, Albania and Macedonia, are poor.
</P>
<P>
"As the refugees have, by and large, been stripped of their
possessions and savings, they are reliant on others --
humanitarian organizations, local residents, recipient country
governments -- to provide for their basic needs," the draft
report said.
</P>
<P>
The financing need was based on an assumption of an influx of
more than 250,000 refugees to the affected countries.
</P>
<P>
Countries, donors and international financial institutions
will meet on Tuesday evening in Washington to discuss the
financing needs of countries affected by the bombing crisis in
Kosovo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
