<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Cracks Down on Car Theft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Federal Bureau of
Investigation (FBI) has arrested more than 200 people in a
nationwide campaign to crack down on car theft starting from
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Federal and state agents targeted theft rings that stole cars
to order, for chopping into parts or for shipment overseas. More
arrests are expected in the next few months.
</P>
<P>
FBI Assistant Director Thomas Pickard said the recoveries of
stolen vehicles are down in recent years and only 14 percent of
auto thefts result in arrests.
</P>
<P>
He admitted that it is "the lowest success rate for any major
crime".
</P>
<P>
"Organized criminal groups turned their attention to interstate
thefts, particularly motor vehicle theft," Pickard told a news
conference.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, 1.4 million vehicles, worth 8 billion dollars, were
stolen and nearly 447,000 were never recovered.
</P>
<P>
Pickard said the FBI and Customs Service estimated that 200,000
of these were shipped overseas for resale.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
